Not everyone does that. Most people just like the style addiction you call a missing leg. Take that. Anything can be a style except those weird 18+ avatars. Hold it. Wait. No, I actually agree with you on that one.

I'm starting to realize that after school naps are time machines. Like this one time I come home from school completely exhausted. I'm like, I'll just lay down for a second, watch some YouTube, relax for a bit. So I grab my phone, lay on my bed, put on a video about some random stuff. I'm watching perfectly fine. Eyes are a little heavy, but I'm good. Then I blink. Just one normal blink. I open my eyes. The room is pitch black. Like, wait, what? I check my phone. It's nine forty seven PM. 9:47. I went to bed at four PM. I've been asleep for 5 hours. My phone is at 3% battery. I have 63 missed notifications. Group chat is going insane. Tyler's like, bro, where are you? Jessica said, are you alive? Marcus literally wrote, I'm calling the police. I'm sitting up in bed, completely disoriented. My pillow is soaked with drool. My hair looks like I stuck my finger in a socket. I try to stand up. My legs are completely numb. I'm stumbling around like a baby deer. I go downstairs. My mom sees me and goes, oh, you're awake. Finally. Finally. She continues dinner was two hours ago. I tried to wake you, but you wouldn't budge. I'm like, mom, why didn't you try harder? She just shrugs. You look peaceful. I didn't want to disturb you. Disturb me? Mom, I have homework. I haven't eaten. My entire evening is gone. Now it's Basically bedtime. But I just slept for five hours. I'm not even tired anymore. So I go back upstairs, try to do homework, but my brain is still in sleep mode. I'm reading the same sentence 17 times, not understanding anything. At 1:00am, I'm still wide awake, staring at the ceiling, knowing I have to wake up at 6:00am. And the cycle repeats because I'll be exhausted tomorrow, come home and do the exact same thing again.

Bro, I just found out something that will absolutely break your brain. You know how people always say live in the present? That's impossible. You have never once experienced the present. Here's why. When your eyes see something, your brain needs time to process it. Same with sound, touch, ever. That delay is around 80 milliseconds, which means by the time your brain shows you what's happening, it already happened. You're living in the past without even realizing it. Scientists prove this by testing how people react to lights and sounds. No matter what, there's always a delay. Your brain just edits it so it feels instant, but it's not. The right now you think you're in is actually a replay. So every single moment of your life is already gone before you experience. You're basically a laggy NPC in a video game, always one step behind reality. And the wildest part, no matter how fast your brain works, you'll never actually catch up. You've never lived in the present, only the past. Like and subscribe, Snoopy.

My kids. Substitute teacher asked, why does your child know classified information about the Pentagon? I nearly spilled my coffee in the school parking lot. What do you mean, classified information? I asked, forcing a laugh. But Mrs. Henderson wasn't smiling. She pulled me aside, lowering her voice. During social studies, Tommy described the Pentagon's underground tunnel system, security checkpoints, code names for restricted areas. He knew things I've never even read about. That's not something a fourth grader should know. My stomach flipped. I tried to sound calm. Maybe he saw a documentary. She shook her head. No, he was too specific. And the way he explained it, like he'd seen it himself. The drive home was unbearable. Tommy sat in the back seat, humming, tapping his Nintendo like nothing had happened. Hey, Buddy, I asked carefully. Where'd you hear about the Pentagon tunnels? He looked up casually. Grandpa told me. He showed me pictures. My knuckles tightened on the steering wheel. Grandpa had died when Tommy was three, and as far as I knew, my dad had been an accountant. He'd never mentioned the Pentagon. That night, I called my mother, mom, did dad ever work at the Pentagon? A long silence on the other end. Finally. Why would Tommy know about that? My chest went tight. Because he's describing things a kid shouldn't know. What aren't you telling me? Her sigh was shaky. Your father made me promise never to talk about his work. Said it was For our safety. But maybe it's time. When she came over, she carried a battered box. Inside were photos, ID badges, documents. All showing my father deep inside secure Pentagon areas. He worked intelligence analysis 30 years. Everything was classified. I flipped through photos of underground facilities I'd never seen before. But how could Tommy know this? My mother's face drained of color. He visits me after school every Tuesday. I thought you knew. My blood ran cold. No. He rides the bus home. We confronted Tommy together. Have you been going to Grandma's without telling me? His shoulders slumped. Grandma said it was our secret. She let me look at Grandpa's office. He showed me the maps on his computer. My skin prickled. Grandpa was

This is the content I've been manifesting, Rebecca continued. Madison, since you're so comfortable with cameras, we'd like to evaluate your potential through a live.

What's the most entitled thing a family member has demanded from you? After seven months of failed attempts, my husband Kyle and I announced that we were finally pregnant. Everyone erupted with cheers except for my sister Jacqueline, who smashed her wine glass against the marble counter. How dare you, she shrieked. You know how long I've been trying for a baby? I deserve to be the first mom. Tried to tell her 19 year olds aren't ready for a baby, but Jacqueline refused to back down. She grabbed her purse then dramatically stormed out yelling that I better abort my baby within 1 week or else she's getting the police involved. The next morning she showed up at our door with printed pages from abortion clinics, shoving them into Kyle's chest while he was still in his boxers. I made appointments for her at 3 different places. She announced to our entire Culdesac, she just needs to pick one. When Kyle tore up the papers, she called the whole family demanding an emergency intervention. That Sunday, 23 relatives crammed into Mom's living room while Jacqueline stood at the fireplace like she was delivering a Ted talk on why I was destroying her life by having a baby first. She actually had a Powerpoint. Our uncle Jeffrey, who's a lawyer, finally told her there's no legal precedent for forcing someone to abort because you want to be pregnant first. She pointed at me with tears streaming down her face and Said if I didn't terminate by Monday, she'd never speak to any of us again. But we called her bluff and all 23 of us told her, see you, Felicia. She actually left sobbing and we didn't hear from her for a long time. And then seven months into my pregnancy, we were having our baby shower. When the door flew open, it was Jacqueline. She walked in with her hand on a massive belly wearing a shirt that said first grandchild loading. Everyone went silent. Mom dropped her cake knife. Surprise, I'm almost due, she announced, spinning around so everyone could see I got pregnant right after that horrible meeting where you all betrayed me. I'm 10 weeks away from giving birth. Nobody was impressed. And when I decided to screw with her and mention my due date, that was 8 weeks, weeks away, her face turned deep red with anger. She grabbed my arm and whispered the dates didn't matter because she'd make sure hers came first, then left before anyone could respond. My mom called me that Tuesday bawling her eyes out. She'd found out from Jacqueline's roommate that Jacqueline had been taking black market labor induction substances.

French. And every time I'm here, he's here, too. That's when Mister Vasquez started laughing. First just a little chuckle, then full on laughing. Natalie and her friends looked at each other confused. I felt my shoulders relaxed for the first time in weeks. This is perfect, Mr Vasquez said, turning his tablet around. According to our system, this man checks in at 5:15 every morning and leaves by 6:45. You have never checked in before 11:00am? Not once. Natalie's face went white. That can't be right, Mr Vasquez kept going. You two have never been in this gym at the same time, ever. It's impossible for him to follow you around because he's gone five hours before you get here. The lobby got so quiet you could hear the machines running upstairs. But my friends saw him following me, Natalie said, her voice shaking. Mr Vasquez looked at Kim. Your friends who come to the noon spin class with you, how could they see something that never happened? Natalie's mouth opened and closed. She had nothing to say. But I know when he's here, she finally said. Oh, now I get it. You've been checking the app, haven't you? Mr Vasquez has pulled up something else on his tablet. You logged into the member app 47 times this week, always between 5 and 7:00am, always checking who's here. The new boyfriend stepped back from Natalie. Wait, you've been tracking your ex? And grabbed Natalie's arm but said nothing. You've Been stalking him through our app while he works out. Then you made up this whole harassment story. Mr Vazquez shook his head. That's a permanent ban. You can't use any of our gyms anymore. Natalie started crying. I wasn't stalking him. I was just checking when he'd be here so I could avoid him. By checking 47 times during his workout. By lying about harassment. No, you're done here. Pack up your locker. I finally spoke, so my membership is fine. Mister Vasquez smiled. You're here every morning at 5:15 like clockwork. You're good, brother. Natalie ran out crying. Kim followed her, trying to calm her down. Through the window, I watched Natalie throw her water bottle at the ground. Mister Vasquez handed me a towel. Your membership's safe. See you tomorrow morning.

My kids substitute teacher asked, why does your child know classified information about the Pentagon? I nearly spilled my coffee in the school parking lot. What do you mean classified information, I asked, forcing a laugh. But Mrs. Henderson wasn't smiling. She pulled me aside, lowering her voice. During social studies, Tommy described the Pentagon's underground tunnel system, security checkpoints, code names for restricted areas. He knew things I've never even read about. That's not something a fourth grader should know. My stomach flipped. I tried to sound calm. Maybe he saw a documentary. She shook her head no. He was too specific. And the way he explained it, like he'd seen it himself. The drive home was unbearable. Tommy sat in the back seat humming, tapping his Nintendo like nothing had happened. Hey, buddy, I asked carefully. Where'd you hear about the Pentagon tunnels? He looked up casually. Grandpa told me. He showed me pictures. My knuckles tightened on the steering wheel. Grandpa had died when Tommy was 3. And as far as I knew, my dad had been an accountant. He'd never mentioned the Pentagon. That night, I called my mother. Mom, did dad ever work at the Pentagon? A long silence on the other end. Finally, why would Tommy know about that? My chest went tight. Because he's describing things a kid shouldn't know. What aren't you telling me? Her sigh was shaky. Your father made me promise never to talk about his work. Said it was For our safety, but maybe it's time. When she came over, she carried a battered box. Inside were photos, ID, badges, documents, all showing my father deep inside secure Pentagon areas. He worked intelligence analysis 30 years. Everything was classified. I flipped through photos of underground facilities I'd never seen before. But how could Tommy know this? My mother's face drained of color. He visits me after school every Tuesday. I thought you knew. My blood ran cold. No. He rides the bus home. We confronted Tommy together. Have you been going to Grandma's? Without telling me, his shoulders slumped. Grandma said it was our secret. She let me look at Grandpa's office. He showed me the maps on his computer. My skin prickled. Grandpa was.

Shocking thing happened at a wedding that made everyone freeze up at once. Everyone knew Blake and Rosalie were going to last forever. Like, seriously, this guy had her military dad laughing so hard he choked. The first time they ever met, while the rest of us had never even heard him speak, Blake invented Random Flower Day, where once a month he'd show up with a bouquet of exotic flowers shipped from different country around the world. Each time our girlfriends would literally use him as an example during every argument. This is what a real man looks like. He organized flash mobs for her birthday, Learned to cook her grandmother's recipes and treated Rosalie like it was her birthday every day. Then Rosalie's mom got diagnosed with Lupus and Blake didn't even hesitate. He switched to night shifts at his accounting firm so he could drive her mom to treatments during the day. He even sold his beloved motorcycle, the one he'd rebuilt with his dad, just to cover the copays when Rosalie's family hit their insurance limit. While the rest of us were complaining about meeting our girlfriend's parents once a month, Blake was at every single family dinner, helping Rosalie's mother cook, helping her dad fix the roof and teaching her little brother to drive. Three years in, Blake proposed. He got down on one knee at her favorite restaurant with her whole family there with her grandmother's ring he'd personally restored and gave this speech. About how she saved him from being a workaholic with no purpose. The whole restaurant started clapping. Rosalie was crying so hard she could barely say yes. The wedding planning was insane. Blake handled everything. She got stressed about vendor calls, seating arrangements, dealing with her crazy aunt who demanded vegan options for everyone. The day finally came. It was a beautiful beach and packed with 300 guests. Rosalie looked incredible walking down that aisle. Her dad tearing up next to her and Blake standing at the altar with tears already running down his face. The efficient Blake's best friend went through all the traditional stuff, the readings, the vows. Rosalie went first and by the end, everyone was dabbing their eyes with. Then came the big moment. Do you, Blake, take Rosalie to be your lawfully wedded wife? The whole beach was silent, everyone waiting for that enthusiastic yes we all expected. Blake looked at Rosalie for what felt like forever. Then he took a deep breath and said, clear as day. Two hours ago, I would have hoisted you up in the air and screamed yes, but now you disgust me and I never want to see you again in my life. He turned and walked away. Rosalie's face went from confused to horrified in about two seconds. She literally collapsed right there in her wedding dress. The best friend stood there with his mouth open. Blake's mom started running after him, screaming his name. Rosalie's bridesmaids rushed. To her, trying to get her to breathe. The whole beach erupted. People were standing up, shouting, asking what the hell just happened. Blake just kept walking, got to the car park where a cab was waiting for him and drove off. Nobody could make sense of it. His groomsmen were blowing up his phone, getting nothing. Rosalie had to be sedated and taken to the hospital. Her brother started calling hospitals thinking Blake had a psychotic break. Then Blake's best man, Tony, finally got through to him that night. What he found out made everyone's anger turn to complete shock. That morning, Blake had logged into his old Hotmail account from high school. He was looking for the first email he'd ever sent Rosalie asking her to meet for coffee. He wanted to quote it in his vows to show how far they'd come from that nervous kid asking her out. But in that old inbox, buried between spam.

My wife left. She said, you'll never manage with the kids alone. Two years later, her daughter asked me to walk her down the aisle. Clara wasn't even my biological daughter. I'd raised her since she was four when I married her mom. But when the divorce got ugly, my ex made it clear I had no legal rights to Clara. I remember the first time Clara called me dad. She was 5. We were at the zoo, and she got separated from us near the monkey exhibit. When the security guard found her, she was crying for her daddy, pointing straight at me. My ex rolled her eyes, but I felt something shift in my chest that day. For eight years, I was the one who drove Clara to soccer practice every Tuesday and Thursday. I helped with homework at the kitchen table until midnight when she struggled with algebra. I taught her to drive in the empty Walmart parking lot, gripping the door handle while she jerked through her first attempts at parallel parking. When she broke her arm falling off her bike at 12, I was the one who held her in the emergency room while they set the bone. She squeezed my hands so tight, she left nail marks. When boys started calling the house, I was the overprotective dad who answered with interrogation questions. But none of that mattered when my marriage fell apart. The custody battle was brutal. Clara, now 16, begged the judge To let her stay with me. He stood up in that courtroom, tears streaming down her face, and said I was the only real father she'd ever known. My ex laughed in court. He's not even her real father. My lawyer tried everything. Character witnesses, photos of school events I'd attended, documentation of every soccer game and dance recital. The judge was sympathetic, but the law was clear. No biological connection, no adoption papers, no rights. I lost. Claire moved three states away with her mom. The day they left, Claire hugged me in the driveway and whispered, I'll find you when I'm 18. I promise. My ex pulled her away, saying it was time to move on from pretend family. For two years, I sent birthday cards that went unanswered, called numbers that were always disconnected. My ex had completely cut me out. I tried Facebook, Instagram, any social media platform I could think of. Every account was blocked or didn't exist. I even hired a private investigator who told me they'd moved twice since leaving. Always covering their tracks. The worst part was running into Claire's old friends at the grocery store. They'd ask how she was doing when she was visiting. I'd have to explain that I didn't know, that I wasn't allowed to know. The pity in their eyes was unbearable. I kept her room exactly the same for six months. Soccer trophies on the dresser, photos from homecoming on the mirror. Her favorite stuffed elephant, On the bed. Friends told me I needed to let go, move on, start dating again. But how do you move on from being a father? Eventually, I packed everything into boxes and stored them in the garage. Not throwing away, just storing. Wait. I started volunteering at the local boys and Girls Club, coaching soccer. These kids reminded me of Claire at that age. Full of energy, looking for someone to believe in them. It helped fill the hole, but never completely. Birthdays were the hardest. Every October 15th, I'd write a card anyway. Pour my heart out on paper, telling her

My parents text me, stop Christmas this year. We want peace, I replied. Perfect. But I did this instead. My parents sent that text on December 3rd, right after I'd asked if they wanted ham or Turkey for Christmas dinner. They've been complaining about hosting duties for years, too much cooking, too much cleaning, too many relatives asking for money. So when they texted stop Christmas, I knew they meant stop me from organising everything at their house like usual. Perfect, I reply. They probably thought I was hurt. I wasn't. I was inspired. I immediately created a group chat with my siblings, my brother Garrett, sister Valentina and youngest brother Nico. Parents want to skip Christmas. Let's give them exactly what they asked for. Garrett was confused. So no presents? No, I typed. We're going to stop their Christmas completely while having the best one ever without them. For 3 weeks, we planned secret. I rented a massive cabin two hours north, big enough for all 14 grandkids, four siblings and our spouses. Valentina handled decorations, hauling in 12 foot trees and enough lights to be seen from space. Garrett organised food, proper feast materials, not the stale cookies and reheated lasagna our parents usually they served. Nico, the baby at 28, handled entertainment, karaoke machine, sledding equipment and a bounce house shaped like a reindeer. We told every relative except our parents, uncles, cousins. Everyone got the new address with strict instructions. Absolute radio silence to mom and Dad. December 24th arrived. My parents posted on Facebook, enjoying our first peaceful holiday in years. No stress, no mess. It had 4 likes, all from their church friends. Meanwhile, at the cabin, my eight year old nephew was teaching Grandpa Joe, Dad's father, how to play video games. My mother in law, who my mom always said was too fancy to associate with us, was in the kitchen making Filipino lumpia with Valentina. Garrett's kids were building a snowman taller than the garage. The best part, my Aunt Patricia, who my parents had been feuding with her five years over a borrowed lawn mower, showed up with her famous chocolate pie, the one my dad requests every year but never gets.

What's the funniest game that turns serious fast? In high school, my friend Arthur started this game called Awkward Questions. The rules were simple. You had to ask your teacher the most uncomfortable but technically appropriate question. Possible points based on how flustered they got. It started innocent. Mrs. Williams, do you think Romeo was taking advantage of Juliet? Five points for her nervous laugh. Mr. Davis, why do we study the Great Depression when we're living through one? Ten points for his visible confusion. But Arthur was competitive. He kept pushing boundaries, hunting for that perfect question that would break a teacher completely. His target was Mr. Wayne, our AP chemistry teacher. Guy was unshakable. Thirty years of experience, seen every teenage trick in the book. Arthur spent weeks researching, looking for the perfect chemistry related question that would crack him. Then he found it. I found out later that Arthur had been digging through old local newspaper archives for weeks. He found a ten year old obituary for Bruce Wayne, age sixteen. Died from accidental chemical poisoning. Arthur connected the dots. Same last name as our teacher, same small town. He found Mr. Wayne's disease. East brother. During class, Arthur raised his hand with that evil grin we all knew meant trouble. Mr. Wayne, I was reading about chemical compounds last night. Is it true that when you mix household bleach with ammonia, it creates chlorine gas? Mr. Wayne froze. Why would you ask that, Arthur? Arthur leaned Back in his chair, savoring the moment. Just curious about the chemical reaction. You know, for educational purposes. The teacher's face went white. Arthur, I need you to stay after class. We thought Arthur had finally won the game. Mr. Wayne looked genuinely shaken. After class, Arthur was practically bouncing with excitement. This was his masterpiece. Mr. Wayne locked the door and sat down heavily. Arthur

Why should the N word be banned? I never thought my black relatives could be so cruel until the day they targeted my mixed daughter, Keisha and told her she was too whitewashed to be related. Throughout the entire barbecue, they mocked her suburban accent, calling her Carlton and Becky. When I pulled my daughter to dance with us to an old school R&B, my uncle laughed and joked, oh, Lordy, lordy, we lost Keisha to them, white folks. Keisha's eyes filled with tears. Later that night, she told me, Mama, they were right. I'm whitewashed, but I'm done with that. Black is beautiful. I'm going to be who I really am. At first, I was thrilled to help Keisha connect with her heritage. That weekend, I took her to the Black History Museum for the first time, talking about our family ancestry. During the tour, she absorbed every word, asking questions about her great grandparents I never heard before. When she asked for more to read, my white husband Mark, bought her the autobiography of Malcolm X, keep her educated and show his support. She finished it in three days and immediately asked for more. The next Saturday, I took her to a downtown braid salon for her first cornrows. The braider ran her fingers through Keisha's hair and smiled. Now that's a beautiful black girl, she said. Keisha beamed like I hadn't seen in years. My family noticed the change, too. They praised her for coming home to Her roots and she'd reply back proudly and Ave. But after a couple months, Keisha became different, harder. Somehow. She started using the N word around Mark aggressively, slamming doors in his face whenever he tried to talk to her. One night at dinner, she looked me dead in the eyes and said, you ain't black enough for marrying him. You sold out our people. I should have corrected her then, but the guilt ate at me. The shoplifting incident should have been my wake up call. When security brought her home after shoving earrings in her bag, she blamed me for teaching her to worship white capitalism. I felt lost. Every time we tried to ground her for doing something bad, she talked about how we were suppressing her for acting black. Even my mother noticed something was wrong. At Sunday dinner, she finally spoke up. This ain't right, Baby. Keisha turned ice cold. All the ones who said I wasn't black enough, now I'm too black, she laughed bitterly. Can't win with y'all. When I weakly suggested therapy, she dismissed it immediately. That's for white people, Ma. Soon she was spending time in dangerous neighborhoods downtown, coming home later and later with new friends who'd eye our house like they were casing it. Mark tried reaching out one last time. Don't speak to me, colonizer. She's fat. I finally set my foot down and threatened Keisha, if you're gonna be like that, leave this house. She, she flipped. Us off and walked out with her friends. Keisha slept over at a friend's who kept us updated until things cooled off. Unfortunately, we'd never recover as a family. Just three days after leaving, my mother called breathing heavily with a shaky voice. Baby, oh, god, baby. Keisha's was spotted with a gang. Your nephew told us they were planning something big on the east side tonight right outside the deli corner store. I hung up and screamed for Mark, trying to set up the GPS. Immediately, we raced to the location he gave us, but the shooting had already started when we arrived. Mark jumped out of the car before I could grab him, before I could tell him to wait for the police. He ran toward the gunfire screaming, Keisha, no. Through the chaos, I saw her lean out the passenger window with a gun and then everything went sideways. Let's flew from another car that came screeching around the corner. Mark was caught right in the middle. He spun like a dancer and fell hard to the pavement, blood pooling beneath him. Immediately, I screamed and rushed over to try to drag his body back to safety. One less white man in the world, Keisha shouted. Stepping out of the car, she walked past his body without even looking down like he was trash on the street. This what real black folk do. Mom, you wanted me to be white, but I chose my people, I pressed My hands against the wounds, trying to hold his life inside him. That colonizer wasn't, never my real father anyway, she continued standing over us. This your fault for marrying him. Through my tears, I screamed.

Night my son was born. The nurse smiled and said congratulations, but my father's face dropped when he saw the baby's eyes. My dad's a geneticist, has been for 30 years. He's the guy who can tell you your ancestry just by looking at your earlobes. So when he saw my Newborn's heterochromia, one blue eye, one brown, he went completely silent. The delivery room was still buzzing with excitement. Jake was crying happy tears, holding our son for the first time. Mom was already posting blurry photos to Facebook with captions like, our beautiful grandson. But dad just stood there staring at the baby like he'd seen a ghost. Jake, I'm here, dad whispered. His voice barely audible over the medical equipment beeping around us. Look at his left eye closely. Jake shifted the baby toward the overhead light. Confused. It's brown. So what? Heterochromia isn't that rare, right? That's not just brown, dad said. And I could hear his voice starting to shake. That's sectoral heterochromia with a very specific golden ring pattern around the pupil. The brown fades to amber in exactly three distinct segments like a sunset. My stomach started dropping. Dad doesn't get excited about genetics unless something's really, really wrong. Dad, what are you saying? He fumbled with his phone, hands trembling as he scrolled through old photos stored in his cloud. Here, look at this picture. The photo showed my deceased brother, Danny at 3 months old, taken right here in the same Hospital. Same exact eye pattern, same golden ring, same brown sectoring that faded to amber, same three distinct segments radiating from the pupil like spokes on a wheel. That's impossible, Jake said, looking back and forth between the photo and our son. Danny's been dead for 5 years. Car accident. Remember, dad was staring at me now and I could see the wheels turning in his scientist brain. Before Danny died in that accident, he was planning to start a family with Sarah when he got back from deployment. He donated sperm to the fertility clinic as backup insurance just in case anything happened to him overseas. My heart was pounding so hard I could hear it in my ears. After three years of failed attempts to get pregnant naturally, Jake and I had finally used donor sperm for IVF 6 months ago. Anonymous donor, they.

You find out your parents wanted you to die. The grocery store security footage showed my face hitting the floor. Blood pooled around my head where I cracked it on the tile. When I woke up in the hospital, I immediately threw up blood. You're literally starving to death, the doctor told me. I tried to sit up, but the room spun violently. I need to get back to work. Rent is due tomorrow. She pushed me back down. You're 16 years old and you weigh 80 pounds. That can't be right. When did you last eat a meal? Three days ago, I think. She looked horrified. Where are your parents right now? In basement, playing their online game, like always. They don't know you're dying? They told me not to bother them unless someone is dead. You almost were dead. Almost doesn't count according to them. She glanced at my chart. You work two jobs and go to school. I work at four in the morning delivering newspapers, then I go to school. Then I work at the grocery store until midnight. That it's physically impossible. Red Bull and gas station pills make it possible. You're taking stimulant. I have to pay rent or we get evicted. Your parents don't have jobs? They quit two years ago to become professional gamers. Are they making money from gaming? I laughed. They've made exactly zero dollars. But they keep saying fame is coming any day now. How much sleep are you getting? My thoughts kept slipping away like water through my fingers. Three hours on a good night, but usually less. Do you ever feel dizzy or confused? Every single day. But I can push through it. She stared at me in disbelief. Parents make you work while they stay home gaming all day? They're trying to build their streaming career. They need my support. She examined my arms, which looked like twigs. You're 40 pounds underweight because you're feeding them instead of yourself. You don't understand. They should be able to follow their dreams after the sacrifices they made for me. My manager, Jimmy, had been sitting in the corner listening. He finally spoke up, looking sick with guilt. I should have said something sooner. This kid has been falling apart for months. He has been seeing things at work that aren't real. The doctor turned to him quickly. What kind of things? Yeah. he was having full conversations with nobody for 20 minutes straight. I felt my face get hot. Sometimes when I'm really tired, I see shadows that aren't there. That's your brain literally shutting down from exhaustion. Jimmy looked broken. And last week I found him unconscious in the freezer. He had been in there for 40 minutes. I had blue lips. I was just resting my eyes. You could have died. But I didn't, so it's fine. The doctor checked my blood work again. Your body is failing and you're still defending them? They're my parents. I owe them everything. You don't owe them your life. Without me, they'll be homeless. Without them, you'd be healthy. The doctor called Child Protective Services and a social worker arrived within an hour. They tried calling my parents 23 times before anyone answered. The doctor put them on speaker so the social worker could record everything. I could hear battle sounds and screaming from their game in the background. This better be important because you just made us lose a ranked match. The doctor spoke calmly. This is the hospital calling about your son who collapsed at work. What does that lazy piece of garbage want now? He's in critical condition from severe malnutrition. My dad exploded. Of course. I should have just let him die when he was born instead of wasting 16 years feeding him. Everyone in the room froze. Your son is hospitalized with severe exhaustion and malnutrition. The doctor said carefully. That lazy waste of space better not miss his shift tomorrow or we'll all be homeless. My mom grabbed the phone. Next, he has to give us $800 by tomorrow or I'm selling everything he owns. The doctor's voice got ice cold. Your child's organs are failing from working to support you. Stop making excuses for that pathetic failure because he can't handle it.

I came back from work. I saw my six year old daughter standing outside, freezing in the snow. I slammed on the brakes and jumped out of my car. Nora, baby, what are you doing out here? She was shivering violently in just her school clothes, no coat. Tears frozen on her little cheeks. Daddy locked me out. He said, I can't come back until you get home from work. My heart dropped it. It was nine PM on a Friday. Jonathan knew I always worked late on Fridays. This wasn't an accident. How long have you been out here? Since you left this morning, she whispered. I scooped her up, feeling how ice cold her little body was, and carried her toward our front door. It was locked. I used my key. Fury building with every step. I found Jonathan exactly where I expected. Sprawled on the couch in his boxers and T-shirt, controller in hand, playing call of duty. The heat was cranking up to 75 degrees. Empty beer cans littered the coffee table. Why was our daughter outside for 12 hours? I tried to keep my voice calm. He didn't even pause his game. She spilled grape juice on my new controller this morning, I told her. Actions have consequences. I stared at him in disbelief. She's 6 years old, Jonathan. She spilled juice accidentally and you left her outside to freeze? Maybe next time she'll be more careful around my stuff. That's when I noticed Nora's Pink backpack sitting by the front door. It was stuffed full, bulging at the seams. Her favorite stuffed bunny was sticking out the top. What's this? I pointed at the bag. Jonathan finally paused his game and turned to look at me. There was something cold in his eyes I'd never, ever seen before. I've been doing a lot of thinking today. While she was outside, he said slowly. This whole family thing isn't working out for me. Nor is too much work, too expensive, too loud. And honestly, I never wanted kids in the first place. The room started spinning. What are you talking about? I'm talking about you taking her and leaving tonight. I already had the locks changed while you were at work. You just got lucky I hadn't switched them out yet. I felt like I was in a nightmare. You're abandoning your own daughter? Nora was still clinging to me, her wet clothes soaking through my work blazer. She was listening to every word, her big brown eyes darting between us. Here's the thing. Jonathan stood up, stretching like this was all perfectly normal. She's not really mine anyway. I mean, yeah, biologically, whatever. But I never signed up for this dad life. You can have her. The casual cruelty in his voice made me sick. This was the man I've been married to for eight years. The man who used to read Nora bedtime stories. Jonathan, she's your daughter. You can't just watch me. He picked up his phone. I already talked to my buddy Steven, who's a lawyer. Apparently, if I just voluntarily give up my parental rights, I don't have to pay child support either. Win, win. My hands started shaking, but not from fear. From rage. I pulled out my phone and speed dialled a number I'd hoped I'd never have to use. Hi, Christine, it's Caroline. Remember that emergency custody documentation we

I told my son exactly what my husband did despite him begging me not to tell. My 14 year old son, Adam has this best friend Dean, who's literally the only reason he still smiles some days. They met last year when we switched schools after my divorce. And Dean was the kid who sat with Adam at lunch when nobody else would. You know how brutal middle school can be for the quiet kids. Dean's dad, Mike, picks him up every day since he's a single dad too. We'd see each other in the pickup line and eventually started talking just normal parent stuff, how the kids were doing in math, upcoming school events, that kind of thing. My, my husband Jake started getting weird about it almost immediately. Jake would make these passive aggressive comments whenever Mike's name came up. Like if I mentioned that Mike told me about some school fundraiser, Jake would roll his eyes and mutter something about how Mike sure knows a lot about what's going on. It was annoying, but I figured he'd get over it. Then Adam got really sick and needed surgery to remove his appendix. It was scary because they found complications and he had to stay in the hospital for almost 2 weeks. Dean visited every single day after school. Sometimes Mike would drive him over on weekends too, since they live pretty far from the hospital. Jake would either completely ignore Mike when he showed up or make These weird territorial comments like when Mike brought Adam some comic books. Jake loudly announced that we already had plenty of books at home. When Mike offered to help with anything we needed, Jake said we were fine and had everything handled. It was embarrassing. Mike definitely noticed because he started keeping his visit shorter. I told Jake to knock it off because his attitude was affecting both boys. Adam could see the tension and Dean started looking uncomfortable whenever Jake was around. Adam finally came home from the hospital about three weeks ago. Everything seemed fine for a few days. The boys were texting constantly and making plans for when Adam felt strong enough to hang out again. Dean even brought over his Nintendo Switch so they could play together while Adam was still recover.

When did you have to choose between your children? I was shopping at Walmart when a kid asked me, sorry, ma'am, can you pretend to be my mom at my parent teacher meeting? I stared at him and he continued. It's just that my mom's an alcoholic and she never shows up. If she misses one more, they'll call CPS. My heart broke as he was almost crying, please, I'll do anything. If you have kids, you'll even take their test for them. He pulled out a crumpled report card showing straight A's. See, I get all A's. I'll do it. Well, I wiped his tears and asked him to tell me about him. He sniffled before saying, I'm Mikey. I know I sound crazy right now, but if mom gets taken away, they'll separate me and my little sister. She's only 7. I can't let her be alone. I pulled him into a hug and gave him my number. That night, I stared at my son Merrick's progress report. Three F's, 2 d. His dad had already threatened to pull him from the team if grades didn't improve. So I texted Mikey at 2:00am. Deal, but strictly business. You take his tests. I play your mom. We met at a Dunkin Donuts the next day to practice. Ask about my grades with concern but not panic. Mention you work two jobs so you can't help with homework much. I nodded, taking notes like this was a corporate presentation. The Conference is Thursday at three thirty PM bring tissues in case they mention my absences. He slid me his class schedule and disappeared. Thursday came fast. Mikey's teacher, missus yet, greeted me warmly. So wonderful to finally meet you, Missus Tyrel. Mikey talks about you constantly. I forced a smile, pulling out the tissues as instructed. I worry about him. The divorce has been hard and I work so much. She squeezed my hand. He's doing beautifully academically, but I do worry about his attendance. I dabbed my eyes perfectly. His father isn't reliable with pickups. I'm trying my best. The meeting lasted 12 minutes. Mikey waited by the exit, handed me merricks algebra test with an a minus circled in red, and we went our separate ways. I started leaving protein bars in random places. I knew he'd find them. He started adding small notes to merricks tests. Tell him the Lakers game was sick or he should try this equation method. By month 3, I knew his coffee order and he knew I parked in the back lot to avoid my ex. When teachers praised my son, I felt oddly proud. When he won the science fair, I clapped louder than necessary. Still, we kept our distance. Then came the call that shattered everything. Missus Tyrel.

My mom poked her head into my room and said, you're not a baby anymore. You'll be fine. She left a box of tissues on my desk and walked away. I Learned to make simple meals by watching YouTube videos at the library after school. Scrambled eggs, grilled cheese, pasta. I started doing my own grocery shopping. When I got tired of waiting for food, I like to appear in the fridge. When they took a family road trip the next summer, I sat quietly in the back seat while they played car games and made jokes with each other. I wasn't invited into the conversation. I didn't try to join. At the rest stops, I bought my own snacks with babysitting money and made sure to sit by the window. One night I overheard my mom on the phone with a friend. She was standing in the hallway not realizing I was upstairs. She said I was so independent now and that she barely had to parent anymore. She sounded proud like she trained a dog to open doors. Another time during dinner, my dad made a joke about how I was like a self cleaning oven. The room laughed. I forced to smile. I never forgot the phrase. By the time I turned 16, I had a plan. I met with my school counselor on my own and asked about early graduation. I doubled up on classes, took extra credit assignments and skipped the junior prom to finish Coursework. They thought I was just motivated. They had no idea I was mapping my escape. That year, I started researching colleges, only out of state ones. I applied for financial aid, scholarships and housing all on my own. I used the school computers to fill out forms. I didn't use their tax documents. I didn't ask for signatures. I figured it out when I got the acceptance letter from a university 900 miles away. I waited until the very last week to mention it. I handed them the envelope at dinner. My mom glanced at the name and said, that's pretty far. My dad grinned and said, guess we raised you too well, huh? There was no family meeting, no debate. They didn't offer to visit the campus with me. They didn't ask about dorms or classes. They just nodded and made vague comments about flights. When the day came, they dropped me off at the airport. My suitcase was half filled with thrifted clothes, secondhand textbooks and a small folder of printed documents. I had $1,200 saved in that shoe box and a prepaid phone plan in my name. They hugged me briefly at the terminal and said, call us when you get there. I nodded and walked straight to the security line. I never called. I blocked both their numbers before the plane took off, not out of spite, not as a message. I just didn't want any more fake check ins or birthday texts that came Four days late on the plane, I looked out the window and didn't feel anything. No nerves, no, no excitement, just the sound of a clean break. When I landed, I took a cab to the dorms, checked in and introduced myself to my roommate like I'd always lived alone. No one asked who dropped me off. No one cared. And that was fine. And in my first week, I opened a checking account, got a campus job at the dining hall and signed up for student orientation events. I made a schedule, posted it above my desk and stuck to it. There was no going back. I didn't burn any bridges. I just stopped crossing the ones they left to rot. College gave me something I hadn't had in years, space that was actually mine. I didn't have to tiptoe around anyone's moods or routines. I didn't owe anyone updates. I just moved, worked and kept going. I got a job at a 24 hour diner a few blocks from campus, took late shifts, sometimes doubles on weekends. The manager liked that I didn't complain and never showed up late. I used the money for rent, books, groceries and a prepaid transit pass. I bought my own winter coat during a clearance sale in October. It wasn't stylish, but it was warm. My roommate asked once why I never called my parents. I told her they were always busy with their own stuff. She didn't ask again on Thanksgiving. I stayed on campus, walked to the corner store and bought boxed Mac and cheese and a pumpkin flavored soda that tasted like regret at Christmas. I helped a friend decorate their tiny apartment with dollar store lights and paper snowflakes. No one from home invited me. No one checked in. At 19, I landed an internship in another city through a connection from one of my professors. I packed my things, found a Craigslist sublet and moved within two weeks. I didn't tell anyone except my landlord and my work study supervisor. There were no goodbyes. No one asked where I went. I updated my resume that summer and decided to start using my grandmother's Maiden name, Lila, not legally, just on paper, on email signatures, applications and my class project credits. It made things cleaner, lighter. It felt like mine. When the internship ended, I didn't go back to campus. I signed a lease on a small apartment, just enough space for a bed, a desk and a table. I bought mismatched dishes from a thrift store and put up blackout curtains. I adopted a cat from the shelter and named her Sparrow. She was quiet, skittish and slept curled up near my bookshelves. We understood each other. For my 21st birthday, I stayed in, made a small cake from scratch, earned the first one, made another, poured a glass of cheap wine and watched an old movie I liked. No phone calls, no messages, just one day. Rolling into the next, a cousin I hadn't spoken to since I was 10 sent me a DM on Instagram later that month. Said something like, why don't you ever come to family things anymore? I didn't answer. Just close the app. That same week, my dad sent me an email with the subject line, hey, stranger. I didn't open it. I deleted it right away, empty the trash and muted the address. A few days later, a Christmas card arrived at my apartment. My name was written in my mom's handwriting on the envelope. Inside was a folded photo of my parents and matching sweaters beside a decorated tree. Their names were signed at the bottom in red ink. I wasn't in the photo. There was no message. They still didn't understand. They thought I was just busy like they'd once been. I graduated at 22 with honors. My name was listed in the ceremony program. My photo went up on the wall in the department building. I wore the gown, stood in line, shook hands and picked up my diploma folder. My boss at the diner sent me a bouquet of flowers. My roommate's parents mailed me a card. My parents weren't there. Not because they weren't welcome, because they weren't informed. That summer, I found a therapist who worked on a sliding scale, paid for it out of pocket.

My girlfriend asked for space to find herself. Then I found her vacation photos with her married ex on our shared icloud account. Three weeks ago, my girlfriend Tessa hit me with the classic speech, I need space to find myself. I'm not breaking up with you. I just need time. Maybe stay with my friend Adrian for a few weeks. No contact would be best. We've been together two years, living together for 8 months. We just booked Christmas flights to visit my family. I helped her pack, told her I understood. A week passed in radio silence. I was respecting her space, going to work, hitting the gym. Then my buddy texted, yo, did you see Tessa's Insta story? There she was with three girlfriends at some beach resort. Caption, sometimes you just need your girls. Girls trip, self care, finding myself. But then I zoomed in. Barely visible at the edge of the frame was a man's arm with a distinctive tattoo sleeve. I know that arm. That's Kieran, her ex from college, the one she told me was completely out of her life. We share an icloud family plan. Stupid. In hindsight, she'd given me access months ago. When her storage was full, I logged into the shared photo stream and found the uncropped versions. Kieran was in every single photo, arms around her, kissing her cheek. Sunset couple photos. The girls trip was actually two couples. Adrian with her boyfriend, Tessa with Kieran. Here's what Changed this from heartbreak to fury. The meta data. These photos started uploading the day before she asked for space. This was planned. I screenshot everything. Then went nuclear. First, I commented on her public beach photo. Great picture. She immediately broke her own no contact rule. Thanks, babe. Miss you. That's when I remembered here.

I told my dad there will be no making up for missing my high school graduation. He was standing in the kitchen with his coffee mug, trying to look like this was just another casual conversation, but I could see him sweating already. Two days before my graduation, he dropped this bomb on me about having to miss it for his stepdaughter's award ceremony in another state. My mom died when I was seven, and he remarried this woman with a 14 year old daughter when I was around 12. Ever since then, I'd basically become invisible in my own house. Emma, his stepdaughter, never knew her real dad, so mine just swooped in and decided she was his priority for everything. When I played basketball in middle school, he'd skip my games if Emma had dance recitals on the same night. Didn't matter if my game was scheduled first. He'd always choose her stuff over mine. When we'd have family movie nights and they'd say, kids can choose, he'd somehow always pick whatever Emma wanted to watch. He'd claim it was more fun for everyone, but really, it was just whatever his little princess wanted. The worst part happened last year when both our refrigerator and shower broke at the same time. Emma's birthday was coming up, and she wanted this huge bar Barbie Dream house thing and some fashion set that cost like $250 total. My dad took money from my birthday fund to fix the house stuff. And make sure Emma got everything she wanted for her birthday. By the time my birthday rolled around, he only had enough left to buy me a 30 dollar steam gift card. He promised me a new monitor and keyboard for my computer setup that my grandparents helped me build. Instead I got 30 bucks and a sorry buddy. Next year will be better. So when he told me he was skipping my graduation to watch Emma get some award, I was done. I looked him straight in the eye and said, there's no making up for that. He can forget about being included in my life going forward.

The longest menstrual cycle you've ever had. I was sitting on my boyfriend's lap when my coochie started bleeding. Silas helped me put a tampon in, but I soaked through it in just 20 minutes. We rushed to the E R, and when I bled through the examination table paper three times, they insisted on keeping me overnight. The hematologist actually said this shouldn't be possible, while I just sat there shaking. The ride home was silent, except for my apologies every time we hit a bump and I felt another gush. For two weeks, he kept making me these protein smoothies every morning, packed with iron for the blood loss. But the bleeding somehow got worse, and I was soaking through overnight pads in 30 minutes. When I mentioned this to Silas, he got defensive and said I was being ungrateful. His voice had this edge that made me shut up immediately. By day 23, I was going through a box of super tampons every two days. Silas had started this weird notebook, writing down time stamps and flow levels, and when I asked what it was for, he said, documentation in this flat voice that made my skin crawl. I'd catch him staring at me sometimes with this expression I couldn't read, like he was waiting for something. My mom stopped inviting me over after I bled through her couch, and the way she looked at me like I was diseased makes me want to cry. The gynecologist Prescribed birth control pills to stop the bleeding, but they made it 10 times worse. And when I called Silas, crying from the bathroom floor, he seemed almost excited, asking about the color and consistency. That's when Relina, his ex girlfriend, messaged me on Instagram. My hands were trembling as I read. We need to talk about Silas. It's about your bleeding. We met at a coffee shop, where she pulled up medical records on her phone showing she'd had unexplained bleeding for two months. It started right after.

Someone say in court that made you burst out laughing. When my daughter was 16, she got rear ended by a drunk driver while stopped at a red light. The guy was clearly wasted, failed three sobriety tests. But somehow his expensive lawyer was trying to blame my daughter for the accident. Crash left her with a concussion and whiplash. She missed two weeks of school and had to quit her job at the local coffee shop because she couldn't handle the physical demands anymore. But this lawyer was determined to prove she was somehow at fault. During the deposition, he kept asking the same questions over and over, trying to confuse her or get her to contradict herself. My daughter has always been sharp, but head injuries can affect your memory. So I was worried about how she'd handle his aggressive tactics. Lawyer starts with this condescending tone. Now, Miss Johnson, you claim you were completely stopped at the intersection, correct? Yes, sir. The light was red. But how can you be absolutely certain you were stopped? Isn't it possible you were still slowing down? Because my car has something called brakes and I use them. The stenographer smiled, but the lawyer wasn't amused. He kept pushing. You were on your phone at the time of the accident, weren't you? No, I wasn't. Come now, you're a teenager. All teenagers are on their phones constantly. Surely you were texting someone. I wasn't on my phone. I find that very Hard to believe what teenager isn't on their phone while driving? That's when my daughter looked him dead in the eye and said, the kind whose parents actually taught her how to drive responsibly. Maybe if more adults acted like adults instead of getting drunk and driving into teenagers, we wouldn't need to have these conversations. The room went completely silent. The lawyer's face turned red, but he kept going. Let's talk about your alleged injuries. Concussions are very convenient because they're impossible to prove, aren't they? Actually, they showed up on my CT scan. But I'm not a doctor. Are you? I'm asking the questions here, young lady. Right. But you just asked me if concussions are impossible to prove. And I'm telling you mine was proven by medical imaging. So either you, you don't understand how CT scans work or you're asking questions you already know the answers to just to waste everyone's time. Our lawyer was trying not to smile. The other guy was getting flustered. Miss Johnson, isn't it true that you've been milking these so called injuries for attention and to get out of school? Yes, because nothing says fun teenage experience like massive headaches, memory problems and having to quit the job I loved. I definitely gave myself a concussion just to miss my AP chemistry test. The sarcasm was thick and even the court reporter was stifling a laugh. But the lawyer wasn't done. He pulled out a photo on his phone and Showed it to her. This is a picture from your Instagram account posted 3 days after the accident. You're smiling. If you were really injured, would you be posting happy photos? My daughter looked at the photo, then back at him with this completely deadpan expression.

When did your friends realise you weren't starving yourself? We're halfway through freshman year and my friends still grab my wrist to show people how their fingers overlap or joke that I could share my metabolism with them. Not kidding. Last week my roommate Leah literally put extra fries on my plate when I wasn't looking. Because someone needs to feed you, babe. Finding this friend group three months into college felt like finally breathing. They adopted me instantly. Leah pulling me into their booth at the dining hall, Sophie looping her arm through mine at parties. At every party they joke I was their pocket sized friend. Leah makes comments like eat a burger, skinny! Whenever we go out. For months. It was relentless but weirdly affectionate. You're gonna blow away. Real women have curves. Bones are for dogs. Every meal was commentary. How are you full already? Must be nice to eat whatever you want. from their guy friend group literally picked me up with one arm once just to prove he could. But it felt like belonging. Like finally having friends who cared enough to tease me. Besides bringing up my celiac seems dramatic. I'd rather take the skinny jokes than be the friend who needs special accommodations. Then three weeks ago, something shifted. The comment stopped. No more eat a burger jokes. No more grabbing my wrists. Instead they got weird, careful, like they were walking on eggshells. Leah started buying extra snacks for the Room, casually leaving them on my desk. So he stopped making the metabolism jokes, replaced with random compliments about my personality. Olivia began suggesting restaurants with lots of options. When we went out Thursday night, I'm coming back early from Biolab, and I hear them through the door. Our whole crew is in there. Leah, Sophie, Olivia, Jade, Madison. They never hang without me. Saturday at the pre game before everyone else shows up. Leah saying we have to be supportive but direct. The signs were all there. Jade says she never finishes meals, goes to the bathroom right after eating. She's getting thinner. My heart stops. They think I'm bulimic. Madison add something about nutrition labels and restrictive behavior. Leah's voice gets soft. Talking about doing this with love. They're planning an intervention for me. I text Sam from home about what I just heard. She asks what they could possibly be staging an intervention for, and when I tell her they think I'm bulimic, she points out the obvious. It's because of my celiac. But they don't know about that. She tells me to just tell them. But I have a better idea. I'm going to make a point. Saturday arrives. I've been at the library all day, giving them time to set up. At 5:45, I hit up the only gluten

I went to my friend's house, but the problem is he had a few girls over. The girls were extremely gorgeous and it was hard to ignore them. We sat down for dinner, but it looked like the girls really hated me. After dinner, we played some basketball together, but again, the girls seemed to not like me as they never passed the ball to me. As the game was about to end, my friend slipped and broke his leg. He screamed in pain and I immediately drove him to the hospital. On the way there, he would not stop complaining about how painful it is. And after 30 very painful minutes, we finally arrived at the hospital. After he was taken care of at the hospital, I drove him back home and he said to me, thanks for everything, bro. I just need one more favor. Could you please get my slippers from upstairs? My feet are freezing. So I went upstairs and found two of the girls lying naked on the bed. I told them, your friend sent me up here to have with both of you. Confused, they said, there's no way, he said that you're lying. So I shouted downstairs, hey, bro, both of them. And he shouted back, of course, both of them. What's the point in fucking one?

My fiance dumped me for a better man her family chose. She threw the ring at me. You're pathetic. Keep your cheap ring. Two years later, she's losing it. After seeing me happy with my successful business and my soulmate, I proposed with a ring I saved 6 months to afford. She cried happy tears posted about forever on social media. We lived in my 600 square foot apartment eating takeout on my futon. And she always said none of the money stuff mattered. Her parents never said they hated me outright, but her father would ask about my little computer project like I was a kid with an imaginary friend. Family dinners were me being the punchline. The end started at a family dinner where her dad had invited his business associates and their sons, Ivy League guys with Goldman Sachs internships. Then they brought out Brody, just made junior partner at a top law firm. Princeton undergrad, Yale Law. Brooke was suddenly fascinated with his work, laughing at his jokes, showing more interest in his career than she'd ever shown in mine. A week later, she showed up at my apartment. I need stability. I can't keep waiting for you to figure it out. I need someone who's already there, someone like Brody. Then her mask slipped. Your 29 playing with computers like you're 19. Brody owns a condo downtown. He doesn't have to save up for months just to buy a decent ring. She yanked off the Engagement ring and threw it at me. Here, take your cheap ring back. Brody's getting me a real one from Tiffany's. You know what's pathetic, I said, pretending to love someone for four years while secretly keeping score. At least I'm not wasting my life chasing some impossible dream. Brody is picking me up at 8, she said, grabbing her purse. Two days later, Instagram official with Brody caption, found my forever. My startup crashed. A month later, I moved in with my friend Kai, started driving Uber Eats to survive. The lowest point, king up a delivery at a cafe where they were sitting outside. Brody saw me first. Well, well, still delivering food. I see Brooke smiled as I walked away. I heard him dodged a bullet there, didn't we? And Brooke laughed. That night I deleted social media and went into rebuild mode. Four hours of sleep. Uber Eats during the day, stocking shelves at night, coding whenever I could. I evidenced to B two b software AI powered contract analysis for law firm. Boring work that solved a real problem. Small firms were drowning in paperwork. Our software analyzed contracts in seconds instead of hours. Within months, we were scaling fast landed contracts with top firms, opened offices in London and Singapore. Beautiful irony. Our biggest market was corporate law, exactly where Brody worked. Our a I tools were making junior associates obsolete. The first time I saw Brooke again was at an industry.

Happened when someone tried to copy your signature look and failed miserably. I've been going to Antoine for six years. Six years. He was the only person in the entire city I trusted with my platinum pixie cut, this very specific shade that took us 18 months to perfect without completely frying my hair. It wasn't just blonde. It was this pearl white situation with subtle silver undertones that caught the light differently depending on the angle. People literally stopped me at Trader Joe's to ask about it. So when I walked into the salon that Tuesday for my touch up and saw Rebecca Thornton in Anntuan's chair, I didn't think much of it. Rebecca was, well, she was that woman who drove the white Range Rover and always parked across two spots at the gym. We'd never spoken, but she'd stare at me sometimes, that weird calculating stare. Antwan was sectioning her hair. When he saw me, his face went pale, like actually pale. Hey, Victoria, you're early. No, I'm not. I'm actually five minutes late because someone took forever at the Starbucks drive through. I laughed. Settling into the waiting area, Rebecca's eyes met mine in the mirror. She smiled this tight little smile. Antoine is giving me your look, she announced just like that. Not a similar style or inspired by. She literally said your look. I remember laughing because what else do you do? Oh, that's flattering. I guess Antoine wouldn't make eye contact with me. Jenny, his assistant, kept refilling my water like her life depended on it. Something felt off. Here's the thing about my specific colour. An.

Boyfriend wanted me to pretend we weren't together at his work party. My boyfriend Nathan told me this while we were getting ready for his company holiday party. Tonight we need to act like we're not together, he said while messing with his watch. I stopped putting on my makeup and look at him. What? Just don't tell anyone you're my girlfriend. Don't hold my hand. Don't stand near me. I couldn't believe what I was hearing. We've been together for two years. He let out this annoyed sigh like I was being ridiculous. My boss only promotes single guys. He thinks relationships make you weak, less focused. I've been telling him I'm single since I started gunning for this promotion three months ago. I felt my stomach drop. Three months of lying about me, he said. Everyone brings plus 1 so it would look weird if he came alone. But I had to pretend to be someone from his apartment building. The promotion decision was Monday. I looked at him in the mirror and felt something shift inside me. I put on my earrings real slow. Okay, Nathan, whatever you need. The second we got there, Nathan walked in way ahead of me like he didn't even know me. I headed straight to the bar where his coworker Brian was getting a drink. I don't think we've met, Brian said with a friendly smile. I'm Nathan, neighbor from his building. It was the cover story Nathan wanted. Brian smiled. Bigger and got me a drink. We were talking for about 20 minutes when he asked, are you seeing anyone? I looked over at Nathan, who was pretending I didn't exist. No, I'm single. Brian's whole face lit up. Wanna meet my buddy Louise from accounting? He waved over a guy from across the room. Louise was actually really charming and kept touching my arm while we talked. Nathan showed up at the bar acting like he just needed a drink. Nathan, meet this gorgeous woman who lives in your building. Louise was excited. Nathan had to shake my hand like we were complete strangers. Nice to meet you, he said. And I could hear how mad he was. You too, I said back. Louise jumped right back in. I was just about to get her number. He handed me his phone. I typed my number in while Nathan stood there, his jaw clenching. About 10 minutes later, Nathan's boss came over to our group. Who's this lovely lady, he asked with this big smile. She's single and lives in Nathan's building, Louise announced, looking pretty proud of himself. The boss's eyes got all bright. Nathan, you seeing this while you're focused on work, Louise is out here meeting beautiful women from your own building. Nathan forced out this fake laugh. His boss kept going, though, this is what I mean. You stay single, you stay hungry. Relationships kill ambition. No offense. He turned to me when he said that. Last part, none taken. I agree completely. I was looking right at Nathan when I said it. The boss just wouldn't stop. Nathan, here is my best example. Three months without a single date. That's dedication. That's why he's getting promoted. Monday, everyone raised their glasses to toast Nathan's promotion. I raised mine, too. To staying single, I said, staring straight at Nathan. His hand was literally shaking when he took a drink. Louise asked me to dance after that. While we were on the dance.

You're not my real dad, and you never will be! My stepson screamed. You're just some pathetic loser my mom settled for because she was desperate and couldn't do better. I remained calm. You're three hours past curfew on a school night, I replied. God, you wish you were my dad, don't you? It's actually embarrassing watching you try so hard. You'll always be nothing to me, so stop trying to be my dad. I looked at this kid I'd raised since he was 8 years old. Okay, then I'm not your dad anymore. He laughed out loud at that. Good. Maybe now you'll stop humiliating yourself trying to parent someone who literally couldn't care less about your pathetic existence. The next morning, Brett came downstairs with his backpack, expecting his usual ride to practice before school. But I just kept drinking coffee and reading my tablet. I'm ready to go now. I looked up, confused. Where exactly? Baseball practice, obviously. I have to be there by 6:30. Why would I drive you anywhere? I'm not your dad. Brett stood there stunned for a full 10 seconds before his face turned red. Are you seriously doing this right now? Doing what? I'm just respecting the boundaries you established last night. He missed practice and had to run laps for an hour at the next one while his teammates watched. When Friday came around, he stood in my office doorway waiting for his weekly allowance. Where's my money for this week? I'm not giving money to random teenagers who happen to live in my house. You seriously aren't giving me my allowance? Why would I give you money when you made it clear I'm not your dad? He stormed back back upstairs without another word. When he got food poisoning at school the following Monday, the nurse called me first. You need to pick him up because he's very sick. I'm not his dad, Brett explained. I'm just his mother's husband, so you'll need to contact his actual parents. They called his mom, who was in an important meeting and couldn't leave. So Brett spent six hours vomiting in the nurse's office until school ended. Then he had to take the bus home. Brett's championship game was the next week, and he stood in my bedroom doorway that morning looking almost panicked. Dad, please come to my game today, because I really need you there. Why are you calling me dad now, when last week you said I was just some pathetic loser your mom settled for? I didn't mean it like that. And you know how important this game is for my future. I'm not wasting my time going to some random kids baseball game. Red's team lost the championship, and he struck out twice with college scouts watching. His mom told me later he kept looking up at the stands between innings, trying to find me. Prom season arrived, and Brett approached me in the kitchen looking desperate while I made dinner. Look, I know I really messed up, but I need your help with prom expenses, like the tux rental and tickets. That's what dads do for their kids. And you established I'm not your dad, remember? Please, just this once, can we pretend things are normal? This is really important. You said I was pretending to be your father for eight years. So now I've stopped pretending, just like you wanted. When his girlfriend's parents asked why I wasn't helping with photos or contributing to the

My brother in law tried to move into my inherited cabin without permission and showed up with a moving truck. I inherited a beautiful lakeside cabin from my grandfather three years ago and it's become my sanctuary with my husband Nathan, where we escape city life on weekends. Nathan's younger brother Dylan has always been the family problem child, dropping out of college twice, unable to hold jobs and making poor financial decisions while his parents, Carol and Dennis, continue enabling him with money and excuses. Six months ago, Dylan started dating Melissa, a single mother with a three year old daughter named Sophie. And they've been living in a cramped apartment in a rough neighborhood while struggling financially with her part time grocery store job and limited child support. The problems began when Dylan started making pointed comments during family gatherings about how lucky we were to have such a beautiful cabin sitting empty most of the week, joking about how wasteful it was not to use it more often while clearly fishing for an invitation to move in. The situation escalated when Dylan and Melissa showed up at our apartment unannounced, asking detailed questions about local schools and job opportunities near the cabin, while Melissa's eyes lit up looking at photos of the spacious rooms and deck overlooking the water. When Dylan casually asked if we ever rented to family, I firmly explained that we didn't rent it to anyone because it was our personal retreat. But the Pressure intensified when Carol organized a family meeting with a detailed presentation about how Dylan could help with property maintenance in exchange for housing while providing better security and opportunities for Sophie. Throughout this coordinated campaign, I felt cornered by manipulation designed to make me look heartless, with Carol claiming my grandfather would have wanted the cabin used to help family in need despite never having met him. While Nathan remained mostly silent and failed to strongly support our boundaries. After we definitively refused their request, Dylan cornered me in our apartment lobby, revealing they'd already given notice to their landlord and told Sophie about the move because they were so confident we'd eventually agree, accusing me of being selfish and cruel for prioritizing comfort over a child's well being. The family pressure campaign intensified with angry calls from Carol and Dennis expressing shock that Dylan had to approach me directly, while Nathan began questioning our decision and suggesting compromises, despite my firm stance that temporary arrangements with people like Dylan first stay temporary. The emotional manipulation reached its peak when Melissa called crying about Sophie's excitement and fears for her safety, revealing Dylan had proposed and they'd be getting married, which explained why the family pressure had intensified as they tried to secure better housing for their future daughter in law and step granddaughter. The breaking point came when I went to the cabin alone for a peaceful weekend to clear my head, only to wake up Saturday morning To the sound of vehicles in my driveway and discover.

While my sister looked through the kitchen, she suddenly screamed, did someone eat my brownies? Just one, I admitted from the couch. And that's when Piper's face went from confused to absolutely horrified. She grabbed the counter and her whole body started shaking. Just one? Just one. Her voice cracked like she was about to have a breakdown. She started frantically checking the brownie pan, counting under her breath while her hands trembled. The whole family slowly gathered in the kitchen, because we definitely demolished those brownies. Mom had found them cooling on the rack when Piper went to her friend's house and cut them up for everyone, thinking Piper had made them for the family. They were these super fudgy chocolate squares with a weird aftertaste, but we figured she'd tried some new health food recipe she found on TikTok. Who ate them? She was practically hyperventilating now, looking at each of us like we'd committed murder. Please tell me you only had tiny pieces. Please tell me you didn't finish whole brownies. But we all knew nobody takes tiny pieces of brownies, especially not when they're still warm from the oven. My little brother finally spoke up, chocolate still on his face. Mom gave them to us after dinner. We thought you made them for dessert, since you're always baking for your bake sales. Piper's knees buckled, and she had to grab the kitchen island to stay standing, her face draining of all color. How many? How many Brownies are gone! Her voice was getting higher with each word. About three quarters of the pan was empty. They were kind of dense anyway, dad commented, patting his stomach. Then suddenly, Winston excused himself. Piper was already on her phone, her fingers flying across the screen. Mom came closer to see what the panic was about. Out as soon as Piper whispered something to her. I've never seen my mother move so fast. Mom's hand flew to her mouth, her eyes bulging, and she actually backed into the refrigerator. You made those in our kitchen! Mom yelled, not even trying to be quiet. With the regular baking pans. The two of them were having this frantic back and forth while we all stood there trying to figure out what we'd eaten. My younger sister was already googling

Wife pushed for an open marriage, said you won't have girls lining up for you anyway. Now she's having a nuclear meltdown watching me get all the attention while she gets none. Rachel and I have been married for six years. Around year 4, things got stale. She started coming home late, barely acknowledging me, heading straight for showers. I'd sit with dinner getting cold, watching her spend an hour decompressing upstairs. She got into self help podcasts and growth work. Instead of helping, she pulled away more. Our apartment became this weird zone where we just coexisted without connecting. Then came our anniversary. We were on the couch with takeout when she said we need to talk about us. I want an open marriage, she announced. Monogamy feels unnatural to me. I stared thinking it was a joke. It wasn't so you want permission to cheat, I asked. It's not cheating if we both agree, she said. It's ethical, non monogamy. Then came the part that killed me when I asked if that meant I could see other women too. She laughed. Don't be so dramatic. Besides, it's not like you'll have girls lining up for you anyway. You haven't exactly been fighting them off all these years. That's when I knew our marriage was dead. She didn't just want to sleep with other guys. She wanted to make sure I knew I couldn't do the same. She mentioned her coworker Vanessa had an open marriage and was living Her best life. I was exhausted from being the only one trying, so I said fine and set ground rules. No emotional attachments, complete honesty first. Rachel jumped in immediately. That same weekend, two hookups back to back. Came home talking about feeling alive and free. Meanwhile, I was mentally planning the divorce, but I didn't rush out. I hit the gym, got back into rock climbing, updated my wardrobe, reconnected with friends. Not to make her jealous. I'd forgotten what it felt like to actually like myself. Women at the gym started conversations. Old friends hit me up. My phone started blowing up with DMS from women I barely knew. Met Lily at an art exhibit. Creative, funny, actually listened.
