Here's the thing nobody tells you about getting sober. Sometimes you fail. Sometimes you fail repeatedly. Four days ago, I'd found out my ex husband was getting remarried. To my former best friend. The one who'd been so supportive during my downward, who held my hair back when I was sick, who promised to help me get better. she's been helping herself to my husband while I Was in rehab. I bought a bottle of wine, sat in my car outside the liquor store for an hour, just holding it. Finally opened it, took one sip, and poured the rest out in the parking lot. But one sip? After six months of sobriety hits different. I've been buzzed for 20 minutes off that single mouthful, crying and laughing at how pathetic I've become. That was four days ago. No alcohol since. But the judge was staring at me with eyes that had seen every excuse, every lie, every desperate attempt at manipulation. She knew something. Someone had seen me with that bottle, reported it. Small town gossip traveled faster than light. I'll take the test, I said quietly. My lawyer grabbed my arm. You don't have to do this. It's not legal protocol. It's fine, I said, though my hands were shaking. The bailiff approached with a device. The courtroom was silent except for the scratching of the court reporter's keys. I could feel everyone watching. The prosecutor who'd pushed for jail time, the victim impact coordinator, the other defendants waiting their turn. My A A. Sponsor sat in the back row. She'd driven me, believed I was still clean. I blew into the device the longest three seconds of my life, waiting for those numbers to appear. The bailiff looked at the reading, then showed it to the judge. 0.00. Judge Reeves leaned back in her chair. Interesting. Now tell me about four days ago. Miss Torres. My throat closed up. How did she know? I don't understand. My nephew works at Miller's Liquor. She said he called me. Described a woman who looked exactly like you, buying a bottle of merlot, sitting in the parking lot for an hour, then pouring it out. He was concerned

During an argument, my fiance sneered, know your place. You should be grateful that I lowered my standards for you. I replied, you're right. Then I ended everything in worst way. I still remember the exact words. Page looked me dead in the eye during an argument and sneered, know your place. You should be grateful I lowered my standards for you. The silence after that line was louder than her voice. I just come off a 12 hour shift diagnosing electrical faults in a Mercedes, cash tip still in my pocket, my hands still stained from the job that kept both of us housed and she reduced all of it to dirt under her fingernails. We were in her apartment. Her apartment she like to call it, though I paid more than half the bills. She stood in the kitchen in a two hundred dollar yoga set looking polished, rehearsed, like she'd been waiting all day to deliver the speech. Embarrass me, she pressed on, voice sharp. My friends ask what you do and I can't tell them. You're a mechanic. Do you know how humiliating that is? Look at yourself. Those hands, that smell of oil. I have a future. You don't. My parents think I'm insane for lowering my standards this much. Her words should have hurt. Instead, something clicked like a wire tightening, sparking, then snapping clean. I smiled. You're right, I told her. She blinked. What? You're absolutely right. You should be with someone better. Someone who deserves you. I grabbed my keys. I'll help you with that. She froze, stunned, waiting for me to beg. But I walked out without looking back. The next morning at the shop, Rye, 30 years in the game, grease stained legend, took one look at me and smirked. You dumped the princess, huh? Other way around then. Best news I've heard all week, that girl was poison. Word spread fast. The guys agreed. A woman ashamed of honest work isn't worth bleeding knuckles for. But Paige wasn't done. She started showing up at the shop, at the grocery store, acting surprised, demanding private talks. I ignored her. Then came the texts, the late night calls, the social media pity posts about supporting your man through struggles. I saved every screenshot, every voicemail. Dean, my oldest friend, told me to document everything. He was right. The housewarming barbecue was the turning point. I just closed on my first home. The.

What's the worst announcement your school ever made? I was a junior at Oakridge when they installed those cheap PA speakers that crackle so bad you can barely understand anything. the ones where every announcement sounds like it's coming through a drive through speaker from 1992, third period, Miss Peterson's history class. We were half asleep watching some dull documentary when that horrible feedback noise hit, the kind that makes your teeth hurt. Attention, students and faculty. It was Principal Winters, but his voice sounded off. Not the usual someone's in trouble tone, more like he was reading a hostage note or something. My pencil froze mid doodle. Due to circumstances beyond our control, all students must remain in their current classrooms until further notice. This is not a drill. I repeat, this is not a drill. The room went dead silent. Even Tyler, who literally slept through the fire alarm last month, sat up straight. Someone dropped a textbook and everybody jumped. Miss Peterson walked to the door and quietly locked it. Her hands were shaking so bad she dropped the keys twice. I'd never seen her scared before. This was the woman who broke up a huge fight during homecoming without blinking. Is this like a shooter thing? Whispered Emma next to me. My stomach dropped to my feet. We'd had those Alice drills before, but this felt different, way different. The speaker crackled again. Teachers, please check your emails immediately. Do not share the contents. With students. Miss Peterson grabbed her phone and I swear all the color drained from her face like ghost white. Everyone away from the windows, she whispered. Now and close the blinds. We huddled against the far wall between the bookshelves. Aiden tried peeking through the blinds, but Miss Peterson practically yanked him back by his hoodie. Is anyone getting anything on their phones? So he asked. I checked mine. No signal. Everyone else, too? Total dead zone, like someone had flipped a switch outside. We heard sirens, lot of them getting closer than the sound of heavy boots in the hallway running. The PA system came on again, but this time it was Vice Principal Garcia. Her voice was shaking, too. Teachers, please identify any students who rode bus No. 17 this morning and Mark them on the Google form that was just shared. Jason raised his hand slowly. That's my bus, he said. His.

I embarrassed my husband for saying I baby trapped him. So my husband and I had our first kid when we were pretty young. I was 21, he was 22. And look, it wasn't planned. I had that birth control implant thing in my arm, the one that's supposed to last like three years. We'd been together since we were 17 and I'd had that implant the whole time we were sleeping together. Four years, zero issues, and suddenly I'm pregnant. The doctor had to take the implant out once we found out it happens sometimes. Apparently birth control isn't perfect. When I told him I was pregnant, he was shocked, but he stepped up. We decided to keep the baby. His family didn't have much money and we were living in one of my parents rental properties at the time because rent was cheap for us. My family is pretty comfortable financially. Nothing crazy, but we're doing okay. His family was struggling. He didn't even have his driver's license yet because he couldn't afford a car. But none of that mattered to me. I loved him and we were gonna make it work. Fast forward seven years, we're married now, been married for three years. We bought a house together, though I put down the deposit because I had savings from working through college. We have three kids total. Life is busy and chaotic, but it's good. I thought we were happy. Last week we went out for dinner. With some friends. There were six of us total. Just a casual Friday night thing at this Italian place. We all, like, everyone's drinking, having a good time, telling story. My husband had a few beers and he was getting louder and more talkative like he does when he drinks. Then out of nowhere, he starts making jokes about our relationship. We got together young, how crazy it was that we have three kids now, normal stuff. But then he says, yeah, I'm pretty sure she baby trapped me. Honestly, he said it with this laugh like it was funny, like it was just another joke. The entire table went quiet. I looked at him and I could feel my face getting hot. Friends all looked uncomfortable as hell. One of them, Katie, literally put her wine glass down and stared at her plate. I said, what the hell are you talking about? He shrugged and took another sip of his beer. I mean, think about it, we were together for four years, no problems. Then suddenly you're pregnant. It's weird timing, don't you think? I just stared at him. I couldn't believe what I was hearing. This man, the father of my 3 children, my husband, was accusing me of intentionally getting pregnant to trap him in front of our friends while drunk. I felt so humiliated, but I was also pissed. So I said, oh, okay, let me get this straight. I baby trapped you for what exactly? Your money. He didn't say anything. Just looked at me. I kept going because you.

What did someone say in court that made you burst out laughing? When my daughter was 16, she got rear ended by a drunk driver while stopped at a red light. The guy was clearly wasted, failed three sobriety tests. But somehow his expensive lawyer was trying to blame my daughter for the accident. Crash left her with a concussion and whiplash. She missed two weeks of school and had to quit her job at the local coffee shop because she couldn't handle the physical demands anymore. But this lawyer was determined to prove she was somehow at fault. During the deposition, he kept asking the same questions over and over, trying to confuse her or get her to contradict herself. My daughter has always been sharp, but head injuries can affect your memory. So I was worried about how she'd handle his aggressive tactics. Lawyer starts with this condescending tone. Now, Miss Johnson, you claim you were completely stopped at the intersection, correct? Yes, sir. The light was red. But how can you be absolutely certain you were stopped? Isn't it possible you were still slowing down? Because my car has something called brakes and I use them. The stenographer smiled, but the lawyer wasn't amused. He kept pushing. You were on your phone at the time of the accident, weren't you? No, I wasn't. Come now, you're a teenager. All teenagers are on their phones constantly. Really? You were texting someone? I wasn't on my phone. I find That very hard to believe. What teenager isn't on their phone while driving? That's when my daughter looked him dead in the eye and said, the kind whose parents actually taught her how to drive responsibly. Maybe if more adults acted like adults instead of getting drunk and driving into teenagers, we would need to have these conversations. The room went completely silent. The lawyer's face turned red, but he kept going. Let's talk about your alleged injuries. Concussions are very convenient because they're impossible to prove, aren't they? Actually, they showed up on my CT scan. But I'm not a doctor. Are you? I'm asking the questions here, young lady. Right. But you just asked me if concussions are impossible to prove. And I'm telling you mine was proven by medical imaging. So either you don't understand how CT scans work or you're asking questions you already know the answers to just to waste everyone's time. Our lawyer was trying not to smile. The other guy was getting flustered. Miss Johnson, isn't it true that you've milking these so called injuries for attention and to get out of school? Yes, because nothing says fun teenage experience like massive headaches, memory problems and having to quit the job I loved. I definitely gave myself a concussion just to miss my AP chemistry test. The sarcasm was thick and even the court reporter was stifling a laugh. But the lawyer wasn't done. He pulled out a photo on his phone and Showed it to her. This is a picture from your Instagram account posted 3 days after the accident. You're smiling. If you were really injured, would you be posting happy photos? My daughter looked at the photo, then back at him with this completely deadpan expression.

On my wedding day, my mom texted, don't expect anyone to show. Then I saw the group photo, all of them on a private beach in Maui. I stared at my phone in disbelief. My entire family had ditched my wedding for a vacation. The caption read, finally together like I didn't exist. But here's what they didn't know. For years, I've been quietly bankrolling their lifestyle. The family business cards all linked to my accounts, Mortgage Co signs, my credit, the Lake House Utilities, auto pay from my bank. I've been the invisible ATM funding their perfect lives while they whispered that my wife wasn't their kind of people. So I sent one text back, perfect timing. Then I called my attorney. Within an hour, I'd cut off every shared account, cancelled every auto payment and revoked access to everything. The secondary property my sister lived in, she was using my credit for the rate. Not anymore. It started small. Day 3, the dealership called about a bounced car lease. Day 5, the office building sent late rent warnings. By week 2, the group chat was pure chaos. Can someone cover the Lakehouse utilities? My card got declined for Scottsdale. Does the company still cover insurance? They were scrambling, but still no apology, just confusion about why their money fountain suddenly dried up. Then my sister called, first time since the wedding. Not congratulations or sorry we missed it. Just you can't do this to us. I didn't even Answer just blocked the number. But the real fun was just begin. See, I'd forgotten about one little detail. My dad's precious boat, the 40 foot yacht he loved showing off at the Marina every weekend. Guess whose name was on the insurance policy? Week 3, I got a call from the Marina. Sir, your boat insurance was declined for non payment. We need it removed by Friday or it gets impounded. I could have warned him. Should have maybe. Then I drove to the Marina Thursday night with my wife and a bottle of champagne. We sat on the dock and watched them tow away Dad's pride and joy. My wife raised her glass. New beginnings to expensive lessons, I replied. The group chat exploded. The next morning, my aunt was practically screaming in all caps, the boat is gone. Who didn't pay the insurance? Dad called me 17 times. I let every single one go to voicemail. Each message got more desperate. Son, please call me back. There's been some mistake. We can work this out. Work what out? That they skipped my wedding for cocktails on a beach. My mom tried a different approach. She showed up at my office unannounced, tears streaming down her face. Security called up to ask if I wanted to see her. Tell her I'm in Maui, I said. The security guard paused. Sir, she says she's your mother. Not anymore. But the nuclear option came when my uncle called. Uncle Rick The family mediator.

My downstairs neighbor thinks I'm having an affair. Started about two months ago. I work rotating shifts at a hospital lab, sometimes days, sometimes overnight. Sometimes I'm there for doubles when we're short staffed. My car leaves at random hours. I come home looking like death. And I'm weirdly private about my schedule because honestly, who wants to hear about blood samples at 7:00am to Janet from 2B? I'm clearly sneaking around on someone. First hint was when she stopped me in the laundry room. You work such interesting hours, she said with this pointed, knowing look, heavy emphasis on interesting. I just nodded, grabbed my clothes and left because I had to sleep before my next shift. Then she started tracking me, like actively watching. I'd see her curtain move every single time I left. At eleven PM she'd suddenly need to check her mailbox right when I stumbled home at 6:00am in my scrubs. Once she was taking out trash at 2:00am. The trash can was empty. My friend Dave came over one night to help me move a couch. Big guy, looks like he lives, left around midnight because he had work. Early next morning, Janet caught me in the hallway, stepped right in front of me. I'm not one to judge how people live their lives, she said, actually touching my arm. But you need to be careful. These things always have a way of coming out. Someone always gets hurt. I was genuinely confused. What Things she gave me the sad sympathetic smile like I was a wounded animal, patted my arm twice and walked away shaking her head. I stood there with my coffee like what the hell just happened? Escalated. She started leaving notes under my door, little folded papers with messages like thinking of you during this difficult time and you deserve to be happy, whatever that looks like. One just said be safe with a heart drawn on it. I genuinely thought maybe she was going through something. I asked if she was okay once. He looked at me with pity and said, I should be asking you that. Then my sister visited for the weekend. We went out for dinner, came back around ten PM laughing about something stupid from when we were kids. Janet was in the hallway watering the plastic plants at ten PM in almost complete darkness she looked at my sister who's taller than me and has bright red hair, then looked at me with this expression of pure disappointment, just slowly shook her head and went back inside. My sister noticed immediately.

Monday morning, we all showed up to find the cafeteria doors chained shut. The sign read, closed until further notice due to food waste and disrespect. This wasn't some fancy school with multiple lunch options. We only had one cafeteria. The nearest gas station was a mile away and leaving campus during lunch was explicitly forbidden. Principal Miss Blade made an announcement during first period, her voice dripping with satisfaction. Due to the disrespect shown to our lunch staff on Friday, cafeteria will remain closed until the perpetrator comes forward. The athletes were the first to struggle. The football team had morning conditioning. The swimmers had practice at 5:00am. They were burning thousands of calories with nothing to replace it. Kids started sneaking granola bars, but Miss Blade caught on. Within hours, she sent an email to all teachers, confiscate any food immediately. Students need to understand actions have consequences. A group of student council kids, the responsible ones who never got in trouble, went to Miss Blade's office to reason with her. She sat behind her massive desk, arms folded, looking almost pleased. This is a collective responsibility situation, she said. When one person damages our community, we all feel the impact. Someone will eventually come forward. But Miss Blade, people have medical conditions, she smiled. This is a valuable life lesson. By Tuesday, things were deteriorating. Kids with low blood sugar were getting shaky and dizzy. Teachers were getting nervous. But Miss Blade called it building character through Adversity. I watched my friend Jason, a diabetic, have to go to the nurse's office three times to test his blood sugar because he couldn't eat on schedule. The nurse looked furious but helpless. Wednesday was when I knew something had to give. Midge collapsed during chemistry. The tea teacher, Mister Stank, caught her before she hit the floor. And you could see the rage on his face as he called for help. Parents started calling, lots of parents. Miss Blade sent out a mass email about teaching responsibility and preparing students for the real world. And because this was rural Alaska, there was no other school in the district. That's when Sophie had her brilliant idea. Sophie was this quiet junior who'd never caused problems, but she was also the daughter of a lawyer and the granddaughter of a woman who'd been in the school board for 20 years. She gathered about 15 of us behind the gym after school. If they wanna play stupid games, they can win stupid prizes, she he said, pulling out her phone. Everyone, text your parents. Tell them you need them to bring you lunch tomorrow. Not pack it, bring it in person during lunch period. The plan was beautiful. It wasn't against any written rule. Parents were technically allowed to visit campus. And if our.

I started canceling on my best friend 5 minutes before every single plan we made. Elliott texted me, sorry, man, just not feeling it tonight at exactly seven fifty five PM when our reservation was for eight PM I've been dealing with Elliott's last minute cancellations for almost 3 years now. The concert tickets I bought two months in advance that cost me $90 each got wasted because he texted honestly, too tired to deal with the concert tonight an hour before doors opened. The hiking trip we planned for my birthday turned into me driving two hours alone to the trailhead because he called from bed saying, dude, I'm too tired. I stayed up until 4:00am playing video games. Every time I tried to make plans with him, there was maybe a 25% chance he'd actually show up. I tried talking to him about it, but he just laughed and said, come on, don't be so dramatic. Life happens. Tried being direct after that. It's actually really disrespectful and it makes me feel like I mean nothing to you. He got defensive and said stop being such a girl. I said I was sorry. It wasn't even just Elliot anymore. My other friends had started treating plans with me the same way after watching him get away with it for years. One friend bailed on helping me move with a last minute text that said actually really hungover. Another canceled on concert tickets an hour before with a not In the mood tonight. The fuck final straw was my birthday party. I bought food and drinks, cleaned for three hours and sent reminders to everyone. Elliot texted at 6:20 saying, sorry bro, I'm really comfortable on my couch right now. Gonna skip tonight when he was supposed to be there at 6:30. Three other people sent similar messages. Within 10 minutes, I sat there alone with enough snacks for 12 people feeling completely worthless. When I explained what happened to my sister, the only person who showed up, she started laughing in disbelief. She grabbed a beer from my party cooler and said, why do you keep showing up for people who don't show up for you? I picked at the frosting on my birthday cake because that's what friends are supposed to do. She shook her head, no. You know what you should do? Start canceling on them. Give them exactly what they give you and watch how fast they suddenly understand what respect means. So when Elliott texted me asking to try that restaurant again, I said absolutely and we agreed to meet there at 7. He texted me at 6:45 saying leaving in 5. At 6:58, I texted back, hey, something came up. Can't make it tonight. He responded immediately with, are you serious? But I didn't reply until Saturday with my bad, let's reschedule. We rescheduled for Wednesday and five minutes before we were supposed to.

My brother forced our whole family to hit 10,000 steps a day until I discovered what he was really doing at 2:00am. I was 22 and perfectly content playing video games after my Best Buy shifts, when my older brother called a family meeting about our health crisis. Fresh off his promotion to regional manager at his insurance company, he decided we all needed his level of discipline. Starting tomorrow, we're all joining this fitness challenge app, he announced, waving his phone like Moses with the tablets. 10,000 steps every single day, or you get marked as failing in front of the whole family. Mom protested that her arthritis made walking painful, but he cut her off with exercise helps arthritis. That's just laziness talking. mentioned his 12 hour warehouse shifts were already physical enough, and my brother actually laughed in his face. Walking around a warehouse isn't real cardio, dad. Then he targeted me directly, and you sitting at that register eight hours a day is basically signing your own death certificate. Forced us to sink our trackers right there in the living room, adding us to his family accountability group, where everyone could see everyone else's stats in real time. The app sent achievement notifications for hitting goals and public shame alerts when someone fell behind. This is about loving each other enough to stay healthy, he said. But the way he configured alerts for every single thousand steps look more like surveillance than love. The torture began. Immediately, as I got seven shame notifications before lunch because I'd only walk 2,000 steps during my morning shift, while my brother's tracker showed 8,000 from supposedly walking around the office that night, I spent an hour walking circles around our neighborhood like a zombie. Just stop the alerts from coming. Within days, mom was dragging herself to 5:00am water aerobics before her hospital shift because it was the only class she could make. Dad dropped $200 on orthopedic shoes and gave up lunch with his work friends to pace walk alone. By week two, the messages turned personal with gem

When did you realize your family wasn't actually happy? I was 12 when I found the wrong birthday cake in our fridge. It said, happy birthday, Olivia in perfect pink frosting. Problem was, I'm Maya, and I had no idea who Olivia was. Mom rushed in when she caught me staring at it. Said the bakery messed up, that they'd fix it later. But her voice got all shaky and weird. She kept looking at the cake like it was gonna bite her. That night, I heard her crying on the phone with someone named Steven. She kept saying, I can't do this anymore, and I miss her too much. When I asked who Steven was, she said it was nobody important, just work stuff. But work doesn't make you sob like that at midnight. I started paying attention to things I'd never noticed before. Like how my parents would get super quiet whenever other families talked about having multiple kids. How my mom would sometimes call me Olivia by accident and then pretend it never happened. Or how there were baby pictures in our house that didn't look quite right. The baby in those photos looked like me, but different somehow. Wrong nose, different eyes. And when I looked closer, the dates were wrong, too. So I went digging through my mom's closet while she was at work. In the back, behind her winter coats, there was this beat up cardboard box. Inside were hospital bracelets, baby clothes in A size I'd never seen. And photos labeled Olivia in my mom's handwriting. Same hospital where I was born, but three years before I was born. The baby looked exactly like me. Same curly hair, same chubby cheeks. But she was wearing clothes I'd never owned. And smiling in places I'd never been. When mom got home, I confronted her with the box. She just stood there holding her car keys, staring at the photos scattered on my bed. Then she sat down and started crying again. That's when she told me the truth. Olivia was my sister. My older sister who died when she was only 14 months old. S I D S, she said. Sudden infant death syndrome. One morning, she just didn't wake up. You were our miracle baby, mom whispered. Our second chance. We wanted to start fresh, to not live in the shadow of losing her. So we never talked about Olivia. We thought it would be better for everyone. But it wasn't better. It was worse. Suddenly, everything made sense.

Has anybody ever tried to truly ruin your life? I worked at Miller Honda. Nothing fancy about me. I wasn't one of those guys in suits playing mind games. I just showed up early, stayed late, and Learned every feature of every car on the lot. The numbers didn't lie. I was top seller three months straight. That's when Shane noticed. Shane was the manager's nephew. This guy thought he was hot stuff because his uncle got him the job. He'd brag about being born to sell cars. But when customers came around, he just lean on his desk scrolling Instagram. While I was closing deals, he was posting selfies. When my sales kept beating his, Shane got nasty. Instead of trying harder, he decided to mess with me. First week of April, I finished this huge sale. Four cars for one family. The Johnsons bought a civic for their daughter and a cord for mom, a pilot for family trips, and a ridge line for dad's construction business. Biggest sale I'd ever made. Shane watched the whole thing from the break room window. Didn't even fake a smile. Monday morning, everything went wrong. HR called me in. Someone reported me for harassing customers. Anonymous tip. They said I was making inappropriate comments to female buyers. Complete garbage. I'd been nothing but professional. One phone call to the Johnson family cleared that up fast. Missus Johnson told HR I was the most respectful salesman she'd ever dealt with. Then my Schedule got messed up. No more weekend shifts when foot traffic was high. No more Tuesday evenings when people shopped after work. Just dead hours on Wednesday mornings and Thursday afternoons. I asked my manager about it. He apologized. Blamed the new computer system, promised to fix it. Nothing changed. Two weeks later, I came home to find two CPS workers on my porch. My stomach dropped. They said they got a report about child neglect. Someone claimed I was leaving my three year old son, Danny, alone while I went to work. They had specific details. They knew Danny's daycare name and said it was fake. They knew what time I dropped him off. They knew everything. I was shaking. My wife started crying. We showed them Danny's enrollment papers, his daily reports. Photos of him playing with other kids. The workers were professional but thorough. They had to inspect our house. They had to interview Danny. The whole thing.

At a family meeting, my parents casually mentioned they would use my inheritance to pay off my brother's debts. I just let them talk because they had no idea. I'd already transferred all my assets into a trust fund they couldn't touch. Walking into my parents house that evening, the tension was thick. My dad had texted requesting a formal family meeting about my grandmother's estate. My grandmother Martha passed away last month, leaving me a substantial inheritance. She'd been my mentor, teaching me everything about money and financial responsibility. My brother Jonathan was the opposite. While I saved, he spent. Our parents constantly bailed him out. Mom made my favorite lasagna. She only did that when she wanted something. Dad cleared his throat. Alexandra, family is the most important thing. We believe in supporting each other. Mom jumped in. Your brother has creditors breathing down his neck, Jonathan. I made some investments that didn't pan out. Then dad dropped it. We've decided to use your inheritance to clear Jonathan's debts. The casual way he said it left me momentarily speechless. They weren't asking. They decided. You're doing well financially, mom added. You don't really need this money the way Jonathan does. I kept my face neutral. How much? About $250,000, Dad said. I nearly choked. That was likely everything grandma left me. We already spoke to Martha's lawyer, mom continued. Since you're family, it should be straightforward to redirect the funds. They contacted the lawyer before even telling me. Tell me more about these debts, I asked Jonathan. He shifted uncomfortably. Business loans, mostly. Some credit cards. What complications require $250,000? Jonathan snapped. Why does it matter? You're sitting on cash you didn't earn. The least you could do is help family. I excused myself to the bathroom. Passing dad's office, I noticed a folder labelled Jonathan's Finances. Inside were records of previous bailouts totaling over $100,000, none repaid. Screenshots of Jonathan's social media showing luxury vacations, an email from his ex warning about his gambling problem. I took photos of everything. When I returned, I asked calmly, when did these gambling debts start? The room went silent. What gambling debts? Dad asked sharply. We never mentioned gambling. 250,000 is a lot for just business expenses. Jonathan's panic confirmed it. There's something you should know. I talked with grandma before she died about her estate. Dad frowned. Whatever she told you, the will is clear. There's no money in the estate, I interrupted. Mom's face went pale. What do you mean? Six months before she died, grandma transferred everything into an irrevocable trust. The will you're eager to execute is empty. Jonathan

What happened when my parents blamed me for my brother's chaos? When I turned 17, my parents sat me down for an emergency family meeting. You're grounded for the rest of the school year, dad announced. Every disaster in this house happens because you encourage your brother's wild behavior. The flooded basement, the broken fence, our missing cat. It's always when you two are together causing mayhem. I stared in disbelief while my 13 year old brother sat there looking innocent. You're bad influence, mom added. No friends, no phone, no leaving your room except for school. We need peace. My brother nodded sadly. I just want to be good, he whispered, while secretly smiling at me behind their backs. Fine. If they wanted to see what my brother was like without me stopping his insane ideas, they'd learn fast. The first day after my grounding started, my brother decided to help with laundry. He mixed bleach with ammonia thinking it would make clothes super white. The toxic cloud that filled our basement sent mom to the emergency room for three hours. The fire department evacuated our whole block while hazmat teams cleared the poison gas. Just an accident, my brother told paramedics with tears in his eyes while I watched from my window knowing I could have stopped this. But that was nothing compared to day 2. He tried fixing Dad's slow laptop by giving it a proper bath. He dunked the whole computer in our bathtub with soap And hot water. The laptop exploded in sparks that.

A man ran up to me and asked, can you hold this? Yeah, sure, I say, because I'm just sitting on a park bench minding my own business. And the guy looks stressed. He shoves this black duffle bag into my hands and takes off running. Doesn't ask, doesn't explain, just runs. The bag hits my lap and it's heavy, like seriously heavy. I try to call after him, but he's already gone, disappearing around the corner like he was never even there. I look down at this bag, like, then I look around. There's a woman walking her dog, a guy pushing a stroller, a jogger with headphones in. Nobody's even looking at me. Nobody saw what just happened. And I need a witness because if someone accuses me of stealing this thing, I have zero proof. It's not mine. That's when I hear it. Police Siren, distant but getting closer. My heart starts pounding because what if they're looking for this bag? What if they're looking for that guy and I'm the idiot sitting here holding whatever he just dumped on me? I should walk straight to the park entrance, flag down a cop, report it. But then my brain catches up and I realise if they find me with this bag before I can explain, I'm the one getting arrested. I have no idea who that guy was. No name, no description I could actually give that would help. Just some stressed guy in a hoodie, which Describes half the people in this city. The problem is I don't even know what's inside. Opening it feels dangerous because what if it's drugs? What if it's something worse? What if just touching whatever's in there could get me sick or leave my fingerprints on evidence? People are starting to notice me now. I've been sitting in the same spot for 10 minutes wedding staring at this bag like it might explode. A mom with a stroller sees me and immediately steers away from my bench. I watch her glance back over her shoulder. I need to move. I need to do something. But what? I could set it down and walk away, just leave it on the ground and disappear. But too many people have seen me holding it. If it's dangerous and I just abandoned it here, that's on me. If it's evidence and I walk away, I look guilty. The sirens are getting louder, closer. My hands are shaking now. I reach for the zipper because I have to know what I'm dealing with. I have to make a decision and I can't make one blind. My fingers touch the metal pole. I'm about to unzip it when I feel something inside the bag move. Scream. It's embarrassing and loud and I'm not proud of it, but something just moved in this bag. Within seconds, park security is jogging over. What's wrong? I start explaining. Some guy handed me this bag and ran off. Then I. Slowly looked down and said something's alive inside. The security guards face goes.

On the destination wedding weekend, I funded my fiance said, stop acting poor in front of my family. If you can't afford to be generous, maybe we shouldn't get married. I said, you're right. What Emma didn't know was that her dream wedding venue, the exclusive Cliff Top resort in Santorini was owned by my family's hospitality group. I've been running operations remotely under a different last name since college. When Emma found the perfect venue on Instagram and begged me to make it happen, I recognized it immediately. My parents had purchased it three years ago. But when she showed me the price and said, I know it's expensive, but my family expects luxury, something made me stay quiet. I covered her parents flights from Boston, her sister's family of four from Chicago, and her college friends from three different states, 16 people. Then the rehearsal dinner, welcome bags, spa days and the upgraded villa suite Emma insisted her mother needed. The first two days were fine, expensive but fine. Then Thursday night, Emma's mother Patricia pulled me aside at dinner. Emma deserves someone who can provide without hesitation, she said loud enough for the table to hear. My late husband never made her mother think twice about spending. Emma squeezed my hand. Mom's right. I need to know you're ready for our lifestyle. Friday morning, Emma wanted to book a private yacht for the rehearsal day. ‚Ç¨12,000. I hesitated, checking my phone. Are you seriously calculating right now? Emma's face flushed. Sarah's fiance just paid parasailing for everyone. Without blinking, her bridesmaid, Sarah, smirked. Maybe he's having second thoughts about more than just the yacht. That's when Emma delivered it. Stop acting poor in front of my family. If you can't afford to be generous, maybe we shouldn't get married. The tape went silent. Her father looked uncomfortable. Her mother raised an eyebrow waiting. You're absolutely right, I said, standing up. Maybe we shouldn't. I excused myself to the bathroom and called Demetrius, our resort manager. Demetrius, it's me. Guest in Villa 7, Emma Harrison's party. Comp everything immediately. Send it to corporate. Then notify them tonight that due to over booking, they need to relocate by tomorrow at two PM all 16 guests, all 16. Find them availability at Hotel Adriana down the coast. I'll cover one night there as apology. I returned to the table. I need to head back early. Work emergency. Emma's eyes widened. Wait, what? The wedding is in two days? I think we need more time to think about this. I said. You were right at dinner. I was at the airport when my phone exploded. Demetrius had delivered the news at ten PM they're making us leave. Some overbooking issue. The wedding is canceled. Where are you? I landed in London and turned off my phone for 24 hours. Saturday evening, Emma's father called from a borrowed phone. Son, I don't know what happened between you two, but Emma's devastated. This Venue situation made everything worse. Can we talk? I'm sorry, Richard. I think Emma made her feelings clear. Her mother was out of line. Emma's been crying.

Who's the dumbest person you've ever met? Senior year of college, I got randomly paired with the quarterback for our capstone project worth 40% of our final grade. This guy had never spoken to me once in four years, but showed up to our first meeting wearing sunglasses indoors, and immediately said, look, I'm not gonna lie, I don't do nerd stuff. You seem smart, so handle it. I just smiled and said, sure. He looked relieved and left. Here's what he didn't know. I was on academic probation. One more failed class and I'd lose my scholarship and get kicked out. I absolutely needed him to do his part, so I documented everything. Recorded our first meeting on my phone, screenshot every ignored text, even see seed him on emails to the professor requesting deadline extensions because my partner hasn't responded. Two weeks before it's due, he finally texts, oh, we good? I responded, I did my analysis section. You need to do the research section and presentation. He left me on read for 10 days the night before it's due. Eleven PM, my phone explodes. Bro, where's the project? I calmly replied, I sent you the outline three weeks ago. Did you do your part? He calls me screaming, saying I'm ruining his graduation, threatening to make my life hell, telling me his dad donates to the school. I recorded the whole call. Presentation day arrives. Professor asks him to present first. He confidently walks up, clearly planning To wing it and just freezes completely blanks. Tries to read off my section but can't explain anything. Professor's face goes from confused to angry. After two painful minutes, she stops him and asks if he even work.

Apparently booking a seat on a train is not a real booking if someone else decides to sit there. So I was taking the train from Edinburgh down to London for this work conference thing. I booked my ticket like 3 weeks ahead because I'm not an idiot and I know these trains get packed. Got myself a nice window seat with a table because I had my laptop and needed to finish this presentation that was due the next morning, 8:47 b. I even wrote it down. I get on the train with my bag and my coffee and I'm already tired because I had to wake up at like 5:00am to catch this thing. I walk down to my seat and there's these four dudes just sitting there, all of them probably in their 20s, laughing loud. One of them's got his feet up on the seat and the guy in my seat, 47B, he's got his jacket spread out like he owns the place. I check my ticket again because maybe I'm losing it. Nope, 47B, window seat, table. That's mine. Hey, sorry, I think you're in my seat, I say, trying to be polite. The guy looks up at me and goes, nah, mate, we're all sitting together. I blink, okay, but like I booked this seat. It's literally reserved. He shrugs. Trains packed, you'll find something. His friends don't even look at me. One of them is scrolling on his phone. Another one's eating chips. Just zero acknowledgement that they're being total jerks. Stand there for a second because I honestly don't know what to do. I'm not about to drag this guy out of the seat myself. So I wait for the ticket person to come through. Takes like 10 minutes. But finally this older guy in the train uniform comes by checking tickets. Flag him down immediately. Hey, so this guy is sitting in my reserved seat and he won't move. The ticket guy looks at my ticket, looks at the seat number above the guy's head. The little screen literally says reserved, sighs like he's already done with his shift. Sir, this seat is reserved. You'll need to move. The guy in my seat leans back and crosses his arms. I'm sitting with my mates. There's plenty of other seats there, aren't, I say, because I'd already walked through two carriages looking for my seat. The train.

Sister in law pranked me by giving me alcohol knowing I don't drink since I have trauma from it. Now she's paying for the joke no one's laughing at. This all happened last weekend and I'm still reeling from it. I don't drink, never have. My parents were both alcoholics and my childhood was a living hell. I've spent years in therapy working through the trauma, and just the smell of alcohol can trigger a panic attack. My husband Alex knows all of this. His family knows all of this. Every year Alex's family hosts a big summer barbecue. It's usually a fun event. Lots of cousins, aunts, uncles. His sister Clara has always been a bit competitive with me. She's always trying to one up me or make little snide remarks, but I usually just brush them off. I figured it was just sisterly rivalry. This year Alex had to work an emergency shift, so I went alone. I felt a little anxious, but I wanted to support his family. When I arrived, everyone was already there, drinks in hand. Clara immediately came over, all smiles. Hey sis! So glad you can make it. Can I get you anything? I smiled back genuinely and said, just a sparkling water, please. You know me. She nodded, walked off, and returned a minute later with a glass. I took a big gulp. It was definitely sparkling water. I relaxed a little. A while later, she came over again. Another one? I Said yes, please this time. As I took a sip, I immediately knew something was wrong. It wasn't just sparkling water there. There's a distinct bitter taste. Alcohol. My stomach clenched. I looked at Clara. She was watching me, a strange glint in her eye. What is this, Clara? I asked, my voice tight. She just giggled. Oh, nothing. Just a little something to liven things up. She winked. I felt the familiar dread creeping up my spine. My hands started to shake. I could feel my breath catching in my throat. I stood up, pushing the glass away. Clara, you know I don't drink, I said, my voice barely a whisper. She scoffed. Oh, come on. It's just a little bit. It won't kill you. We just wanted to see what would happen if you actually had a drink for once. You're always so uptight about it. Her friends, who were standing nearby, started chuckling. I looked at them, my vision blurring. They were laughing. Laughing at my pain, at my trauma. I felt a wave of not. I mumbled. I have to go. I walked away, trying to keep it together, but my legs felt like jelly. I could hear their laughter echoing behind me as I rushed to my car. The drive home was a blur. I pulled into the driveway, barely made it inside, and collapsed on the living room floor, hyperventilating. It felt like I was a child again, hiding from my parents, drunken rages. Alex got home a few hours later and found me curled up in a ball, still shaking. He immediately knew something was terribly wrong. I told him everything through sobs and gasps. I've never seen him so angry. His face went completely red. He grabbed his phone. I heard him yelling at Clara. A furious, one sided conversation. He told her she was sick, did and that she would never see him again. He hung up and immediately blocked her number. The next morning, Alex called his parents. He explained what Clara had done. His mom started crying, apologizing profusely on Clara's behalf. His dad was quiet, but I could hear the anger in his voice. They told Alex they were mortified and that they would talk to Clara. Later that day, Alex's mom called me directly, saying how sorry she was, how she couldn't believe her daughter would do something so cruel.

My little sister Maya just turned 16 and decided she was too cool for piano lessons. She'd been taking them for eight years with this quiet older woman, Missus Brown, who lived in a tiny apartment above the music store downtown. Maya started complaining constantly about how Missus Brown's apartment smelled like old books and mothballs, about how her piano was this ancient upright that was probably from the 1940s, about how the wallpaper was peeling and there were water stains on the ceiling. I'm completely wasting my time, Maya announced at dinner one night, dramatically throwing her sheet music on the table. Could be making real money with a part time job instead of playing boring scales for some lady who probably charges us 20 bucks because she feels sorry for us. Mom just nodded and said we'd discuss it later, but Maya was on a roll. Do you know what Jenny's piano teacher charges? $80 an hour. And she teaches at the Conservatory downtown with those beautiful grand pianos, not some cramped apartment that hasn't been updated since the Nixon administration. I tried to defend Missus Brown. She's really nice, Maya, and you've gotten so much better. Nice doesn't pay the bills, Maya shot back. Missus Brown wears the same three cardigans every week. The black one, the navy one, and that hideous brown one with the missing buttons. It's actually embarrassing when my friends ask where I take lessons. This went on for weeks. Maya would come Home from lessons and immediately start complaining about something new. The coffee stains on Missus Brown's sheet music, the fact that her apartment was always too cold. How Missus Brown would offer her these stale cookies that probably came from the dollar store. I bet she's never even performed professionally, Maya said one day. Real musicians don't end up teaching kids in apartments above music stores. Last Tuesday, Maya finally wore mom down. Fine, mom said. We'll go tell Missus Brown in person. It's the respectful thing to do. When we got there, Missus Brown was sitting at her piano with tears in her eyes, holding an old black and white photograph. She looked up and gave us that gentle smile she always had. The one that made you feel like you were the most important person in the world. Oh, Maya, perfect timing. I was just thinking about the day I started teaching. Maya couldn't even wait for us to sit down. Actually, missus brown, I wanted to tell you that I'm stopping lessons. I think I've Learned enough, and honestly, I need to focus on getting a real job. Missus brown nodded slowly, still holding the photograph. Of course, dear. You've grown into such a beautiful musician. I'm so proud of how far you've come. That's when Maya said the thing that changed everything. Honestly, I just think I need a teacher who's more successful. Someone who's actually made it in music, you know, no offense.

Sister got me excluded from Christmas because I'm just a plumber. So I cut off her law school money fund. I'm 32, own my own plumbing business and make six figure. Here's my sister. Amanda is 26 and in law school. For two years, I've been covering her full tuition every semester without complaint. But there were signs I'd miss. She never invited me to her law school event even though I was funding them. She changed the subject when friends asked what her brother did. She never introduced me to Craig, her doctor boyfriend of almost a year. The call came a week before for Christmas. My mom told me I wasn't invited this year. No explanation, just it might be best if you sit this one out. I pressed for a reason. She gave vague nonsense about professional appearances and keeping everyone comfortable. Then my cousin Sarah texted me screenshots from the family group chat. Amanda had told our parents that having me at Christmas would make things uncomfortable. She was worried what Craig's family would think about having a plumber at the table. She'd actually written, I just don't want Craig to think our family isn't, you know, educated. Educated while her education existed because her uneducated plumber brother was paying for it. My parents agreed with her. They thought it was reasonable to exclude their own son because my blue collar job might embarrass their daughter's boyfriend. I sat with this for two days, getting angrier. But also clearer. Then I called Amanda. I wanted to talk about your tuition payment. I said it's too soon. Right? Her voice changed instantly, sweet and interested. Oh, yeah. Thanks for remembering. You're still okay to cover it, right? Actually, I've been thinking about what you told mom and dad about how having a plumber brother might embarrass you in front of Craig and his family. Dead silent. That's not who told you that. She finally sputtered. Does it matter? Is it true she tried damage control? Listen, you don't understand. Craig's family is really partic killer. His father's a judge. His mother's on charity board. I just need them to take me seriously. So you pretended your brother doesn't exist because he's just a lowly plumber, but you still want that plumber's money for two.

My girlfriend informed me that her ex was moving into my apartment. You could learn from him, she smirked. I nodded. When she left, I packed her stuff, changed the locks and texted her ex, she's yours now. Her things are at the door. I've been dating Vicky for 14 months. She moved into my place six months ago when her rent supposedly got hiked. Found out later her roommate kicked her out for stealing clothes. The real problem was Chris, her ex boyfriend of three years. She brought him up constantly, comparing everything I did to how Chris did it better. Chris makes this with more garlic or. Chris and I went there once. It rained, but we made the best of it, always with this dreamy smile like she was reliving magical moments. When I finally asked why she mentioned him so much, she got defensive. Are you that insecure? We're just friend. That's when I Learned they were still texting regularly, but I tried to be the cool, understanding boyfriend. Pattern escalated. Every movie, restaurant or trip came with a crisp comparison. I was happier when she wasn't home because I could finally relax without walking on eggshells. Then came the night that changed everything. I was making stir fry when Vicky came home from spin class. Not even sweaty, which was weird for someone who supposedly just did 45 minutes of cardio. So there's this situation. She said, scrolling through her phone, one of my friends, Got kicked out of his place. He needs somewhere to crash for a bit. Who are we talking about? She hesitated. Chris. Your ex boyfriend? Chris, yeah, but he's just a friend now. He's super quiet, super respectful. Then she added with a fake smile, you might actually learn something from him. His king makes yours look like struggle meals. She was trying to move her ex into my apartment where I paid 100% of the rent and acting like I should be grateful for the cooking lessons. I just said okay. I knew right then. I was done. I wanted to see how far she take this. That night she said she was meeting her friend Jen for drinks. I called Jen after Vicky left. Are you meeting Vicky tonight? The pause told me everything. Um, no, I haven't talked to her since last weekend. The moment her car left, I checked the time. Seven twenty two PM I had maybe three hours. I grabbed storage bins and started packing her stuff. Not carefully, just grabbing armfuls and stuffing them in her two.

Mom's, what did your daughter do when she heard you scream at night? Last night I was in the kitchen dancing around, eating leftover pizza when I smashed my toe on the chair leg and screamed. My daughter, Bella comes running. She's 8, cute, tiny, big brown eyes, but wicked smart and just a little evil. She stops in the doorway, tilts her head and whispers, mom, did dad hit you? I laugh. What? No, Bella, your dad was asleep on the couch. She narrows her eyes like Detective Bella just cracked her first murder case. Uh huh. That's what all moms say. She whips out her little notebook. Yes, she has a notebook, starts scribbling like she's building a case file, dreaming night time, dad present, suspicious. Next morning she struts into the kitchen, slams that notebook on the table. Dad sipping coffee, half asleep. Bella points a pencil at him like it's a weapon. Confess. Did you assault my mother with your fists? My husband chokes on his drink. What? No. Bella squints. Then explain the scream. He tries to laugh, but Bella isn't playing. She leans close and says, if you don't tell me the truth, I'll call grandma. Choose wisely. I'm dying inside because she sounds like a mob boss. My husband's begging me with his eyes, but I shrug. Bella grabs his phone and bolts. He's chasing her down the hall yelling, give that back. She shouts, one more move and grandma gets the call. If this kid ever joins the FBI, we're all doomed. At night, chaos hits again. I'm in bed reading and my husband decides to tickle me. Out of nowhere, he digs his fingers into my ribs and I scream bloody murder loud. Bella burst through the door like she's been training for this moment. She gasps, sees dad leaning over me and shouts, I knew it. Before we can explain, she grabs the landline phone and dials grandma. It's 11:30 at night. Grandma picks up half asleep, and Bella yells, come quick, Dad's attacking mom. My husband freezes like a deer in headlights. I'm laughing so hard I can't breathe, which only convinces Bella more. Fifteen minutes later, grandma storms into the house in her robe with a rolling pin. Where is he? My husband throws his arms in the air. I was tickling her. Bella crosses her arms. That's what abusers say. I'm still laughing, trying to explain, but grandma doesn't let him off easy. Tickling your wife at midnight, you got problems, Son. Bella sits there smug like she just solved the case of the century. And the kicker, as Grandma's leaving, Bella leans in slow, looks her dad dead in the eyes and says with that evil smirk, one wrong move, tickle monster, and I'll know.

My rich parents died and left behind a Kahoot quiz to determine who'd inherit their fortune. Mom and dad were worth millions, built their company from nothing, lived in a mansion that looked like it was ripped from Architectural Digest. Every family gathering was a networking event where my siblings would pitch their latest business ideas or drop hints about their financial struggles. The four of us had always assumed we'd split everything equally when they died. We assumed wrong. The lawyer's office was packed. My brother Beckham flew in from Dubai where he was closing deals. My sister Harley interrupted her honeymoon in Bali. My other brother Felix brought his lawyer, already prepared to contest whatever the will said. I came straight from my shift at the hospital where I work as a nurse. Your parents left specific instructions, the lawyer said. Pulling up a projector screen. Your inheritance will be determined by your score on this quiz, a Kahoot game loaded on the screen. Family trivia, 50 questions. The lawyer handed us tablets. This is insane, Beckham said. They can't be serious. Question 1, the lawyer read. What was your mother's middle name? I typed Lorelei. Felix typed Lauren. Beckham and Harley were frantically text sing each other. The results flashed on screen. Only I got it right. Question 2, what was your father's first job? I typed janitor. My siblings put various tech positions wrong, wrong, wrong. By question 10, the pattern was clear. Beckham had three Correct. Harley had two. Felix had four. I had 10. What medication did mom take daily? I knew it was metformin for her diabetes. My siblings didn't even know she was diabetic. Dad's biggest fear? Heights. He told me during our monthly lunches when my siblings were too busy to show up. The name of Mom's chemotherapy nurse? Alyssa. I knew because I went to every appointment. Mom had cancer. Harley yelled, this is bullshit. Beckham stood up. How are we supposed to know mom had cancer? She never told us she did. I said quietly at Sunday dinners, you just never came. The questions got more personal. What made dad cry at his 70th birthday? I typed, when no one but Jocelyn me showed up. Correct. What was Mom's favorite book? The one I gave her last Christmas. My siblings hadn't given gifts in years, just sent assistance with gift cards. When did your parents have their first date? The diner on Fifth Street. Dad told the story every anniversary dinner. I was the only child who attended them. Beckham threw his tablet down at question 30. This is rigged. You obviously help him make this. When did your parents renew their vows? Last summer in their backyard. I was the only witness. My siblings were at various retreats, conferences and yacht parties. What surgery did dad have? In 2,019? Triple bypass. They were all too busy to visit. I took three weeks off work. The final question appeared. What Did your parents value most? I typed, being seen as people, not checkbooks. The final scores flashed me, 48 out of 50. Felix, 7 out of fifty. Five out of 50. Harley, 4 out of 50. The lawyer clicked to the next screen. A video message from my parents appeared. If you're watching this, we're dead, mom said, with her dark humor intact. And you've just discovered that only one of you actually knew us. Every question was something we shared with you, dad added. Every answer was a conversation you chose not to have. Jocelyn gets everything, mom.

voice_to_text: Hey, Elio. Your mom called me asking if I knew where you were. I told her you were in my house, in the bathroom, just to cover for you. But seriously, where are you? It's been a day now. Elio. Your mom's freaking out, and honestly, so am I. She called the police. I haven't told them that I lied for you. I keep telling her you're here, but I have no idea where you are. Please come home. I'm getting really worried. I asked my FA favorite astrology app, Astro App, for advice and it said that I'm a cancer, so I can get really emotional when I feel abandoned. It told me to take deep breaths and focus on grounding myself so I can stay calm and clear minded while waiting to hear from you. Elio, it's been a week. Everyone saying you're missing. Like actually missing. Your mom's been crying non stop and they filed a police report. Where are you? What's going on, Ello? It's been a month now. They still can't find you. I don't even know what to tell people anymore. I got a cat to help with the loneliness, I guess. I named him Charlie. Figured you'd like that. Wish you could see him. She's really sweet. Sleeps with me every night. She and was born on Valentine's Day too. Hahaha. It's been two months since you disappeared. I stopped writing to you because it felt like screaming into the void. Your mom's pregnant. Can you believe that? Guess there'll be another Elio around soon. I miss you so much, Elio. 10 months now. Your sister's almost here. Her name is going to be Julia. I keep hoping you'll walk through the door before she's born. Ello, it's been two years. I know that sounds insane, but part of me still thinks you're coming back. I can't move on from this. Everyone tells me to, but I can't. It's like a piece of me went missing with you. Hey. I need to tell you this. I'm getting married. I found someone who loves me. I think you'd like him. He's the love of my life. And I'm finally getting married. I asked for star rings so you'd be here with me in some way. I miss you more than ever right now. Ilio. It's been five years. I don't know what to say anymore. But I'm still here. They closed your case, the police. No one's looking for you anymore. But I'll never stop. I'm thinking of searching for you on my own, but in secret. Oh, and I'm pregnant. It's a boy. I'm naming him Elio, after you. Hey. Wow. I didn't even realize we're still having this conversation. It's been seven years. My son's been born. Look. I think he looks a bit like you. He's as cute as you were. Or maybe that's just me imagining things. Wish you could see him. Hey, Elio. It's been 11 years. He's turning four. Today. Time flies, doesn't it? Feels like yesterday when I last saw you. He really admires you, you know. I always tell him how great you were as a boyfriend. He says you're still alive, that we're so connected. That's why I feel like you're still around. But I don't know. Sometimes I lose faith in you coming back. I wonder if he's right. I still feel you somehow, Ello. It's been 14 years. My new boyfriend tells me I need to move on. Says I'm holding on too tight. But my son, he still believes you're coming back. He's only a kid, but he has more faith than I do by now. It's been 20 years, Elio. Wow. My boy's nine now. He's getting so big. And guess what? I'm pregnant again. With a girl. She's due in four months, and I'm naming her Jula. Like your sister. Speaking of, your sister moved back in with your parents. She's not doing well. She barely speaks to anyone. It's like everything fell apart when you left. Elio, it's been 25 years. I built the house we dreamed of. Remember that? I also got divorced, though. He cheated on me. Now it's just me, Elio, Julia and the cat. Still waiting for you, I guess. I miss you more than I can put into words, Elio. You have no idea. Every single day. Bria. The fuck you mean I died? I was just having some burger and fries. You're already planning My funeral. Chill. You can now check part two by pressing share. Then more.

voice_to_text: Justin, Emma didn't make it. Womp, womp. What do you mean, womp, womp? You don't even care. She was your girlfriend for two years, Justin. She loved you for two years. Listen, Tammy, this is not my problem. She overreacted and did something irrational. That's on her, not me. Justin, you literally broke her heart. How could you after the two years of her being there for you? When big sis Jessica passed away, that hurt us bad. And she was there for you, making sure you were okay. When you couldn't take me to school because you were too sad to get out of the bed, Emma came to take me. She would always take care of me, like how our big sister would before she passed. She would always buy me food, pack my lunch, and would even come over to watch me and take care of me when nobody was home. She would stay home with me just to play Barbies with me, to make sure I wasn't scared being alone. She was the best girlfriend you ever had. She was the sister I needed after big sis passed away. And now you're the reason why Emma is gone. Because you were selfish and cheated. I don't have time to read a lot. Go cry to someone else. Leave me be. One day you will see. You lost the best thing you had. Stop talking to me, mom. I still can't believe she's gone. I couldn't stop Crying after seeing her in the casket. I know, baby. It broke all of our hearts. We lost a beautiful soul that day. She was the perfect daughter I never asked for. Always taking care of us like she was a part of this family. We will miss her forever. Yeah, everyone will miss her. Except Justin. Justin is so evil. How could he do that to her? I talked to your brother, Tammy, and what he did was absolutely terrible and unforgivable. He should be grounded forever. Sadly, I can't do anything since he's a 20 year old man. Mommy, I really think this is my fault. If I would have just shut my mouth, Emma would still be here. But I decided to be a loud mouth. This is all because of me. Baby. No, you did the right thing. Don't ever feel bad about doing the right thing. Yeah. Mommy, could you at least take me to see Emma again? I miss her so much. I want to play Barbies with her. I wish I could, Tammy, but I'm so tired and I have work tomorrow. Auntie, can you send me a rizz app line so mommy can take me? This will for sure make mommy smile. Say this. My love for you will give you all the energy you need. My love for you will give you all the energy you need. Oh, that's so sweet. You're right. I do have enough energy for one more Trip, meet me at the car. Yay! I'm bringing my Barbies! I'm bringing my new Barbies to come play with you. Emma, I miss you so much. You were the best thing I had in my life. I will never forget you. And I'll keep that promise that we made at your grave that I will come play Barbies with you every single day. I love you so much. Mommy, when will you be back from work? I have to go see Emma again today so we can play Barbies. Yesterday was so fun with her. I was so happy I could spend time with her. Sorry, baby. I won't be able to make it home on time because of this snowstorm. But, Mommy, I made a promise to Emma that I would never miss a day. I'm so sorry, Tammy, but I can't today. Don't be sorry, Mommy. I won't break my promise to Emma. Wait, honey, what do you mean by that? Tammy? Justin, where is Tammy? I don't know. Why are you asking me? You didn't watch over your little sister. I looked over the entire house, and she's not here. And that's my problem. How? Oh, my god. I think she went to Emma's grave. Wait, how would she even be able to walk all the way over there by herself in the snow? No time for questions. Get in your car and drive to the cemetery now. Whatever. Did you find anything, Justin? I looked Around and found nothing. Oh, my god, not my Tammy! Well, actually, I did find this one thing. Two Frozen Barbies in front of Emma's Tombstone. Oh, my god, no!

voice_to_text: What was your most unforgettable run away from home attempt? My parents weren't like abusive or anything, but they were super strict. I'm talking no social media, no hanging out with friends on school nights, and my phone had to be turned in at nine PM every night. Literally medieval torture for a teenage girl. The final straw came after this huge fight about my grades. I've been struggling in math, always hated it, still do tbh and got a D on my report card. My parents flipped. They took my phone for a month, banned me from seeing my friends, and made me spend weekends doing extra math worksheets instead of anything fun. I was texting with my best friend Charlotte at school about how unfair it was and she was like just come stay with me for a few days, my parents won't care. Her family was mad chill compared to mine. Her mom let her have boys in her room with the door closed. I was jealous AF so I decided to run away. Now I wasn't completely stupid. I knew I couldn't just disappear forever. I was thinking like a 3 4 day protest to show my parents they were being unreasonable. Maybe they'd realise how much they missed me and stop being so strict. I packed a backpack with like the Absolute Essentials. Three t shirts, my favourite hoodie, a pair of jeans, some underwear, my school makeup bag, and like $43 I'd saved from Birthday money. I also took this silver necklace my grandma gave me that I thought I could maybe sell if I needed more cash. Teen logic lol. I waited until everyone was asleep, probably around 1:00am. Our house had this super creepy wooden hallway, I literally practiced walking through it for weeks before I ran away, finding exactly where to step to avoid making noise. I felt like a ninja that night, swear to god. The plan was to walk to this 24 hour convenience store about a mile away and call Charlotte to come get me. But here's where everything went sideways. Charlotte's phone was dead. Like completely off. No response. I tried calling her house phone. Yes, they still had one, but her dad answered and I panicked and hung up. So there I was, sitting outside the 7 11 at 2:00am, no ride, and starting to low key freak out. The guy working inside kept giving me weird looks through the window. I was just sitting on the curb trying to figure out what to do when this red sedan pulls up. There were two guys and a girl, probably college age. The girl rolled down her window and asked if I was okay. I must have looked pathetic AF because she immediately offered me a ride. Her name was Melissa and she seems super nice, telling me they were coming back from a party and could drop me somewhere. Now I know this sounds dumb Don't get in cars with strangers and all that. But teenage me was desperate. It was getting cold, and I figured having a girl there made it safer. Plus, Melissa had this really gentle voice and kept saying she just wanted to help. I told them I needed to get to Charlotte's house, but didn't have her exact address. Another brilliant part of my plan. The guys were talking quietly in the front seat while Melissa kept asking me questions. How old I was, why I was out so late, if my parents knew where I was. I started noticing we weren't going towards Charlotte's neighborhood at all. We were heading towards the highway when I pointed this out. The guy driving, Steve, I think, said they needed to make a quick stop first. That's when the alarm bells really started going off in my head. Melissa kept trying to keep me calm, saying they just needed to drop something off with a friend, and then they'd help me find Charlotte's house. But then the other guy, Benjamin

voice_to_text: I was locked inside a bathroom like some kind of stray dog. I didn't even think about running. The colour was choking me, my breath coming shorter and shorter. Finally, I used my foot, hooked the bowl toward me, scooped it up with shaking hands and devoured it right then. It tasted like a five star meal. But before I'd had more than a few bites, a cry for help echoed through the room. Someone else was here, I answered quickly. Suddenly, the light snapped off. No more communication allowed. I dumped out the food, grabbed the metal tray, slammed it against the wall over and over, trying to tell him I'm here, too, too late. My head went dizzy. The food was drugged. I couldn't hold on. Everything went black. Morning cold water splashed my face. They dragged me out for a walk just like a real dog. The chain was gone, but the collar still clamped tight. I saw no one behind me and bolted. Only a few steps. The colour lit up. It tightened around my throat. A warning blared from hidden speakers piercing my ears. The wire fence was right ahead. I grabbed it. A jolt of electricity tore through me, blackness again. When I woke up, I Was back in the kennel. This time another man was inside. I rushed to him, thrilled, asking what was going on. He said he'd been kidnapped, too. We stayed locked up together. Only one thought in my mind, escape. Next day, we were let out, nobody behind us. We pretended to stroll, crept closer to the fence. No electricity this time. We climbed out, ran like our lives depended on it. But just a few steps later, our colours lit up again. It squeezed my throat. I collapsed. The man turned back, trying to drag me along, but the colour took him, too. We both blacked out. When I woke up, a wall separated us. Our chance was gone. That day, the keeper came with dog food. I lay still, pretending to sleep. The man stood up suddenly, snatched the keeper's stick, then with a metal tray, knocked him cold. What are you doing? I gasped. Getting us out. What's the worst thing your sibling did that you secretly understood? Hotel security called my parents at 2 in the morning to say I was burning something in the parking lot. And the security guard dialed the police. Nobody asked why. They assumed my anxiety disorder was finally making me dangerous, exactly like her fiance, Derek, had been warning them. And an hour later, they drove me home in silence and sent me to my room while Derek told them downstairs that I needed to be institutionalized. I could hear every word. She's obsessed. She can't handle Rebecca being happy. This is what happens when you ignore the warning signs. My sister hadn't spoken to me in months because he had been cutting me off from her. At 6:00am, I went to the attic before anyone could stop me. I pulled out the old trunk and started laying everything on the floor. The diary, the Death certificates, the photos. My mom found me there surrounded by papers and something about my face made her call everyone downstairs. I spread the death certificates across the coffee table. Great grandmother Charlotte, married 1949, dead 11 months later, heart failure at 23. Great aunt Louise, married 1972, dead 13 months later, fell down the stairs. Second cousin Helen, married 1998, dead nine months later, car accident. Then I showed them the photos. All four women wearing the same dress in their weddings, three of them even wearing it in their caskets. Then I opened the diary that belonged to my great, great grandmother, Evelyn, married in 1924. I read the final entry out loud. He will kill me tomorrow. So I have sewn my Protection into my wedding dress, my hair, my blood, my words. If I cannot live, neither will his legacy. Every woman who wears this dress will join me. Derek stood up fast and his chair fell over. This is insane. But his voice shook and my dad noticed.

Why do I suddenly speak French? The French tourist next to me on the subway were arguing, and somehow I understood every word, even though I'd never studied French in my entire life. The woman was complaining about her mother in law's cooking, and 30 seconds ago this would have been complete gibberish. Excuse me, I said to them in perfect French that I was shocked to feel coming out of my mouth. Are you speaking French? They stared at me, and the woman asked where I was from. I opened my mouth to say I didn't speak French, but what came out was lion in an accent so authentic. She started asking about specific neighborhoods. I grabbed my bag and pushed through the doors just as they closed. Standing on the platform, my hands were shaking as I pulled up a French news site. Every word made sense, including idioms I shouldn't know existed. I called my mom. Did we ever live in France? Did I take French as a kid? I asked, what? What? No, honey, why would you think that? She said, you know, we've never even left the country. I hung up and went home, where Claire was watching TV with subtitles. She was in her fourth year of French and always had homework spread everywhere. I picked up her textbook and read a passage out loud. Wait, what are you doing? Claire asked me in the TV. You don't speak French? I do now. I Said in French. That's not possible, she said. Say something else. I recited a poem I never heard before about autumn leaves and death. It just came out like it had always been in my head. Claire grabbed her laptop and pulled up a video of someone speaking Rapid Quebec French, which was supposed to be incomprehensible even to some French speakers. What are they saying? She asked. I translated every word, including the slang. Claire stood up and backed away from me. We're going to the hospital, she said. Has anything unusual happened recently? She asked. Any new medications or experiences? Just that psychology study at school three days ago. But that was about memory, I said. What kind of study? She asked. They paid $200 to wear headphones and look at cards for two hours. It was supposed to be about pattern recognition. The doctors exchanged looks and the French one asked to see any paperwork I had. I found the crumpled sent form in my bag and handed it over. She read it and frowned. This isn't from the university, she said. The Burger Institute. Isn't affiliated with your school. But it was in the psychology building. I said we should call the university, she said. While she made calls, I googled the Burger Institute on my phone. One archived webpage from 2,010 mentioned experimental language education. Nothing else existed. The business card the researcher had given me now went to a pizza place. Doctor came back looking concerned. The university has no record of any study, she said. The room you described is a regular classroom. They're sending campus security to check it out. That night, I couldn't sleep. I kept thinking in French without meaning to.
